{"title_page": "KZGD", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = KZGD\n| image            =\n| city             = [[Salem, Oregon]]\n| area             =\n| branding         = ''La Zeta 1390/93.5''\n| slogan           = \n| frequency        = 1390 [[kilohertz|kHz]]\n| translator     = 93.5 K228FN (Salem)\n| airdate          = October 3, [[1934 in radio|1934]] (as KSLM at 1370)<ref name=\"bc79\"/>\n| format           = [[Regional Mexican]]\n| language         = [[Dark (broadcasting)|Silent]] (was [[Spanish language|Spanish]])\n| power            = 5,000 [[watt]]s ([[Daytime (astronomy)|day]])<br>690 watts ([[night]])\n| class            = B\n| facility_id      = 72475\n| coordinates      = {{coord|44|59|43|N|123|04|15|W}}\n| callsign_meaning =\n| former_callsigns = KSLM (1934-2007)<br>KKSN (2007-2009)<br>KVXX (1/2009-5/2009)<br>KWOD (2009-2014)<br>KZZD (2014-2016)<ref name=\"fcc1\" />\n| former_frequencies = 1370 kHz (1934-1939)<br>1360 kHz (1939-1941)\n| affiliations     = \n| owner            = Edward C. Distell\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  = \n| webcast          = \n| website          =\n}}\n'''KZGD''' (1390 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) is an American [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to serve [[Salem, Oregon]], United States.  The station, founded in 1934 as KSLM, is currently owned by Edward C. Distell.  KZGD broadcasts a [[Regional Mexican]] format.<ref name=\"arb1\">{{cite web |work=Arbitron |url=http://www.arbitron.com/radio_stations/station_information.htm |title=Station Information Profile}}</ref><ref name=\"ruf\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Day |work=Statesman Journal |title=Area radio stations alter programming; Some of the talk shows on KFXX will be tough to receive for area listeners |url=http://www.statesmanjournal.com/article/20090504/SPORTS/905040349/1001/NEWS/Area+radio+stations+alter+programming |date=May 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"edr7\">{{cite web |publisher=ESPN Deportes Radio |title=Estaciones afiliadas a ESPN Deportes Radio en EE.UU. |url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/story?id=226774&s=rad&type=story |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=June 2, 2009 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe station was previously assigned the KWOD [[call sign]] by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) on May 29, [[2009 in radio|2009]].<ref name=\"fcc1\">{{cite web |title=Call Sign History |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=72475&Callsign=KZGD |work=FCC Media Bureau CDBS Public Access Database |accessdate=June 2, 2009}}</ref> The station was later assigned the KZZD [[call sign]] on March 31, 2014.\n\n==History==\n\n===The beginning===\nThis station was founded in October 1934 as '''KSLM''', a 100-[[watt]] day-time AM station broadcasting on 1370 [[kHz]] in [[Salem, Oregon]].<ref name=\"bc44\">{{cite book |title=1944 Broadcasting-Telecasting Yearbook |year=1944 |page=144 |chapter=Directory of Standard Broadcasting Stations of the United States |publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref><ref name=End>{{cite book |url= https://archive.org/details/oregonendoftrail00writrich |title= Oregon: End of the Trail |author= [[Federal Writers' Project|Writers' Program]] of the [[Work Projects Administration]] in the [[Government of Oregon|State of Oregon]] |series= [[American Guide Series]] |year= 1940 |publisher= [[Binfords & Mort]] |location= [[Portland, Oregon]] |page= 228|oclc= 4874569}}</ref> Owner Harry B. Read added nighttime operation in 1935.<ref name=\"orh\">{{cite web |work=Oregon Radio History and More |title=KSLM |url=http://members.tripod.com/ke7ggv/nwradiohistory.html |accessdate=March 20, 2009}}</ref>  In May 1937, the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'' made special note that KSLM's careful commercial policy stood \"as a barricade holding questionable advertising material from the ears of listeners\".<ref>{{cite news |work=Christian Science Monitor |title=KSLM Careful In Acceptance Of Advertising |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/csmonitor_historic/access/316587122.html?dids=316587122:316587122&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=May+24%2C+1937&author=&pub=Christian+Science+Monitor&desc=KSLM+Careful+In+Acceptance+Of+Advertising&pqatl=google |date=May 24, 1937 |quote=\"If in doubt-- don't\" is the watchword in the commercial policy of Station KSLM here which stands as a barricade holding questionable advertising material from the ears of listeners.}}</ref> Read had earlier started [[Portland, Oregon]] radio station [[KXL (AM)|KXL]] and would go on to found the Salem Electric [[utility cooperative]] in 1938.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Salem Electric |work=The Info Bulletin |title=Who Was Harry B. Read? |url=http://www.salemelectric.com/bulletin/2008/0108_InfoBulletin.pdf |date=January 2008 |format=pdf |access-date=2009-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326164415/http://www.salemelectric.com/bulletin/2008/0108_InfoBulletin.pdf |archive-date=2009-03-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=Salem Electric |title=Salem Electric History |url=http://www.salem.coop/guide/se_history.aspx |accessdate=March 20, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1937, KSLM was one of several [[Pacific Northwest]] area stations to join the [[Don Lee (broadcaster)|Mutual-Don Lee Broadcasting System]].  KSLM changed frequencies to 1360&nbsp;kHz on April 28, 1939, which allowed for a power increase to 1,000 watts during the day and 500 watts at night.  In 1940, the nighttime signal was raised to match the daytime power at 1,000 watts.  On March 29, 1941, KSLM changed frequencies again, this time to the current 1390&nbsp;kHz.<ref name=\"orh\"/>\n\nHarry B. Read sold KSLM license holder Oregon Radio, Inc., to automobile dealer Paul V. McElwain and partner Glenn E. McCormick for a reported sale price of $69,000 on March 1, 1944. At the time of the sale, it was still the only commercial radio station with Salem as its community of license.<ref name=\"bc44\"/> In May 1959, KSLM increased its daytime signal power to 5,000 watts and switched its network affiliation from Mutual to [[ABC News Radio|ABC]].<ref name=\"bc60\">{{cite book |title=1960 Broadcasting Yearbook |year=1960 |page=A-214 |chapter=Directory of AM and FM Radio stations in the U.S. |publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n===New ownership===\nAfter more than four decades of continuous corporate ownership, Oregon Radio, Inc., sold KSLM to Holiday Radio, Inc., in October 1977 as part of a two-station deal valued at $684,000.<ref name=\"bc79\">{{cite book |title=Broadcasting Yearbook 1979 |year=1979 |pages=C182-C183 |chapter=Directory of Radio Stations in the United States and Canada |publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> The new ownership initially continued the [[middle of the road (music)|middle of the road]] music format that the station had been broadcasting for most of the 1970s.<ref name=\"bc79\"/> KSLM flipped to an [[adult contemporary]] music format in 1982.\n\nIn October 1985, Holiday Radio, Inc., reached an agreement to sell the station along with its FM sister station to Ronette Communications Corporation  for {{nowrap|$1.2 million}}. The deal was approved by the FCC on December 6 and the transaction was consummated on February 20, 1986.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19851008ET) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=82434 |date=February 20, 1986}}</ref> As part of an internal corporate reorganization, Ronette Communications Corporation applied to the FCC to transfer the KSLM broadcast license to Ronette Communications of Oregon, Inc., in February 1986. The transfer was approved by the FCC on February 11, 1986 and consummated on July 17, 1986.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19860206EG) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=85604 |date=July 17, 1986}}</ref> In mid-1986 the station transitioned to an [[oldies music]] format.\n\nJust over two years later, in March 1988, Daytona Group of Oregon, Inc., contracted to sell the station to John E. Grant's 1010 Broadcasting, Inc., for $215,000.<ref name=\"orh\"/> The deal was approved by the FCC on July 15, 1988 and consummated on July 26, 1988.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19880324EE) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=110610 |date=July 26, 1988}}</ref> 1010 Broadcasting, Inc., agreed in February 1992 to sell the station to K-Salem Communications (Greg Fabos, owner) for $151,000.<ref name=\"orh\"/> The deal was approved by the FCC on April 6, 1992 and consummated on May 8, 1992.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19920226ED) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=171019 |date=May 8, 1992}}</ref> The station began replacing live and local [[disc jockey]]s with programming from [[Satellite Music Network]]'s \"[[Kool Gold]]\" oldies format in February 1994.<ref name=\"orh\"/>\n\n===Trouble ahead===\nIn July 1994, K-Salem Communications reached an agreement to sell KSLM to Willamette Broadcasting Corp., Inc.  The deal was approved by the FCC on November 2, 1994 and consummated on December 22, 1994.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19940715EB) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=200980 |date=December 22, 1994}}</ref> The new owners had difficulty finding a new transmitter site for the station after the sale and the station was off the air from late 1995 until early 1997.<ref name=\"orh\"/>\n\nWith the station back in operation, Willamette Broadcasting Corp., Inc., announced in September 1998 that it would sell it to [[Entercom Communications]] subsidiary Entercom Portland License, LLC, for $605,000.<ref>{{cite news |work=Broadcasting & Cable |title=Changing Hands |first=Alisa |last=Holmes |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53123288.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025041314/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53123288.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |date=October 19, 1998 |quote=KSLM(AM) Salem, Ore. Price: $605000. Buyer: Entercom Portland License LLC, Bala Cynwyd, Pa. (David J. Field, president)}}</ref><ref name=\"epr1\">{{cite pressrelease |first=Tom |last=Baker |publisher=Entercom Portland |title=Entercom Announces Purchase of Salem, Oregon Station |url=http://www.entercom.com/newsPage.php?id=18 |date=September 4, 1998}}</ref> The deal was approved by the FCC on October 22, 1998 and consummated on December 14, 1998.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19980903EF) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=273557 |date=December 14, 1998}}</ref>\n\n===Changing callsigns===\nThe station took on a [[sports radio|sports talk]] format as a simulcast of [[Vancouver, Washington]], sister station KFXX (910 AM, now [[KMTT]]), branded as \"The Fan\", just after the sale to Entercom was completed.<ref name=\"epr1\"/>  When 910 AM became oldies-formatted KKSN, KSLM maintained the simulcast and became an oldies station. In January 2007, Entercom dropped KKSN's oldies format for [[talk radio]] as part of a pending sale to [[Salem Communications]] and KSLM began once again simulcasting sports radio [[KFXX (AM)|KFXX]], now at 1080 AM.<ref name=\"fyb\">{{cite web |publisher=Tower Site of the Week |title=The Big Trip 2006, Part III: Corvallis and Salem, OR |first=Scott |last=Fybush |url=http://www.fybush.com/sites/2007/site-070223.html |date=February 23, 2007 |quote=A quick note on KSLM: a few months after our visit, it took the KKSN calls when Entercom turned off the oldies and sold the 910 facility to Salem - the broadcaster, not the city. What's now KKSN 1390 in Salem now relays Entercom's Portland sports station, KFXX 1080.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=[[Statesman Journal]] |title=KKSN 910 sold - changes format |first=Michelle |last=Theriault |url=http://finndxer.wordpress.com/2007/02/20/kksn-910-sold-changes-format/ |date=February 20, 2007}}</ref> After more than 70 years as KSLM, Entercom applied for new call letters for this station in early 2007.  The FCC changed the callsign to '''KKSN''', the call letters of its former sister station and simulcast partner, on February 12, 2007.<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>  To better align it with Portland sister station [[KFXX (AM)|KFXX]] (1080 AM), the callsign was changed again on January 20, 2009, this time to '''KVXX'''.<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>\n\nOn May 1, 2009, KVXX dropped its simulcast of KFXX to begin airing [[Spanish language]] [[ESPN Deportes]] programming in conjunction with [[sister station]] KTRO.<ref name=\"ruf\"/><ref name=\"edr7\"/> The station was assigned the '''KWOD''' [[call sign]] by the FCC on May 29, 2009, after an Entercom-owned station in [[Sacramento, California]], switched to [[KUDL|KBZC]].<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>\n\nOn July 12, 2010, KWOD changed their format to [[English language]] sports, simulcasting [[sister station]] [[KFXX (AM)|KFXX]] (1080 AM, \"1080, The Fan\").\n\nOn March 31, 2014, KWOD changed their call letters to KZZD and changed format to regional Mexican. The change of call sign and format was coincident with Entercom's donation of KZZD's license to the Minority Media and Telecommunications Council, Inc. (MMTC). MMTC, in turn, sold the station to Edward Distell for a purchase price of $75,249; this transaction was consummated on June 20, 2014.\n\nOn September 23, 2016, KZZD changed their call letters to KZGD.\n\n==Former on-air staff==\n[[Peter Courtney]], a member of the [[Oregon Senate]], and since 2003 the President of the Senate, was once employed by KSLM as a [[pundit (expert)|political commentator]].<ref>{{cite web |work=Oregon Blue Book |title=Members of the Oregon Senate |url=https://sos.oregon.gov/blue-book/Pages/state/legislative/senate-images.aspx |accessdate=March 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|KZGD}}\n*{{FMQ|K228FN}}\n*{{FXL|K228FN}}\n*[http://photos.salemhistory.net/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/sj&CISOPTR=289&CISOBOX=1&REC=6 Photo of station owners Bruce Kerr and Lou McCormick Paulus in front of the KSLM building in 1976]\n*[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=44578&.pdf FCC History Cards for KZGD]\n\n{{Spanish Radio Stations in Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Oregon|ZGD]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language radio stations in Oregon|ZGD]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Media in Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = KZGD\n| image            =\n| city             = [[Salem, Oregon]]\n| area             =\n| branding         = ''La Zeta 1390/93.5''\n| slogan           = \n| frequency        = 1390 [[kilohertz|kHz]]\n| translator     = 93.5 K228FN (Salem)\n| airdate          = October 3, [[1934 in radio|1934]] (as KSLM at 1370)<ref name=\"bc79\"/>\n| format           = [[Regional Mexican]]\n| language         = [[Dark (broadcasting)|Silent]] (was [[Spanish language|Spanish]])\n| power            = 5,000 [[watt]]s ([[Daytime (astronomy)|day]])<br>690 watts ([[night]])\n| class            = B\n| facility_id      = 72475\n| coordinates      = {{coord|44|59|43|N|123|04|15|W}}\n| callsign_meaning =\n| former_callsigns = KSLM (1934-2007)<br>KKSN (2007-2009)<br>KVXX (1/2009-5/2009)<br>KWOD (2009-2014)<br>KZZD (2014-2016)<ref name=\"fcc1\" />\n| former_frequencies = 1370 kHz (1934-1939)<br>1360 kHz (1939-1941)\n| affiliations     = \n| owner            = Edward C. Distell\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  = \n| webcast          = \n| website          =\n}}\n'''KZGD''' (1390 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) is an American [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to serve [[Salem, Oregon]], United States.  The station, founded in 1934 as KSLM, is currently owned by Edward C. Distell.  KZGD broadcasts a [[Regional Mexican]] format.<ref name=\"arb1\">{{cite web |work=Arbitron |url=http://www.arbitron.com/radio_stations/station_information.htm |title=Station Information Profile}}</ref><ref name=\"ruf\">{{Cite news |first=James |last=Day |work=Statesman Journal |title=Area radio stations alter programming; Some of the talk shows on KFXX will be tough to receive for area listeners |url=http://www.statesmanjournal.com/article/20090504/SPORTS/905040349/1001/NEWS/Area+radio+stations+alter+programming |date=May 4, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"edr7\">{{cite web |publisher=ESPN Deportes Radio |title=Estaciones afiliadas a ESPN Deportes Radio en EE.UU. |url=http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/news/story?id=226774&s=rad&type=story |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=June 2, 2009 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\nThe station was previously assigned the KWOD [[call sign]] by the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) on May 29, [[2009 in radio|2009]].<ref name=\"fcc1\">{{cite web |title=Call Sign History |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=72475&Callsign=KZGD |work=FCC Media Bureau CDBS Public Access Database |accessdate=June 2, 2009}}</ref> The station was later assigned the KZZD [[call sign]] on March 31, 2014.\n\n==History==\n\n===The beginning===\nThis station was founded in October 1934 as '''KSLM''', a 100 [[watt]] day-time AM station broadcasting on 1370 [[kHz]] in [[Salem, Oregon]].<ref name=\"bc44\">{{cite book |title=1944 Broadcasting-Telecasting Yearbook |year=1944 |page=144 |chapter=Directory of Standard Broadcasting Stations of the United States |publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref><ref name=End>{{cite book |url= https://archive.org/details/oregonendoftrail00writrich |title= Oregon: End of the Trail |author= [[Federal Writers' Project|Writers' Program]] of the [[Work Projects Administration]] in the [[Government of Oregon|State of Oregon]] |series= [[American Guide Series]] |year= 1940 |publisher= [[Binfords & Mort]] |location= [[Portland, Oregon]] |page= 228|oclc= 4874569}}</ref> Owner Harry B. Read added nighttime operation in 1935.<ref name=\"orh\">{{cite web |work=Oregon Radio History and More |title=KSLM |url=http://members.tripod.com/ke7ggv/nwradiohistory.html |accessdate=March 20, 2009}}</ref>  In May 1937, the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'' made special note that KSLM's careful commercial policy stood \"as a barricade holding questionable advertising material from the ears of listeners\".<ref>{{cite news |work=Christian Science Monitor |title=KSLM Careful In Acceptance Of Advertising |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/csmonitor_historic/access/316587122.html?dids=316587122:316587122&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&date=May+24%2C+1937&author=&pub=Christian+Science+Monitor&desc=KSLM+Careful+In+Acceptance+Of+Advertising&pqatl=google |date=May 24, 1937 |quote=\"If in doubt-- don't\" is the watchword in the commercial policy of Station KSLM here which stands as a barricade holding questionable advertising material from the ears of listeners.}}</ref> Read had earlier started [[Portland, Oregon]] radio station [[KXL (AM)|KXL]] and would go on to found the Salem Electric [[utility cooperative]] in 1938.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Salem Electric |work=The Info Bulletin |title=Who Was Harry B. Read? |url=http://www.salemelectric.com/bulletin/2008/0108_InfoBulletin.pdf |date=January 2008 |format=pdf |access-date=2009-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326164415/http://www.salemelectric.com/bulletin/2008/0108_InfoBulletin.pdf |archive-date=2009-03-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=Salem Electric |title=Salem Electric History |url=http://www.salem.coop/guide/se_history.aspx |accessdate=March 20, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1937, KSLM was one of several [[Pacific Northwest]] area stations to join the [[Don Lee (broadcaster)|Mutual-Don Lee Broadcasting System]].  KSLM changed frequencies to 1360&nbsp;kHz on April 28, 1939, which allowed for a power increase to 1,000 watts during the day and 500 watts at night.  In 1940, the nighttime signal was raised to match the daytime power at 1,000 watts.  On March 29, 1941, KSLM changed frequencies again, this time to the current 1390&nbsp;kHz.<ref name=\"orh\"/>\n\nHarry B. Read sold KSLM license holder Oregon Radio, Inc., to automobile dealer Paul V. McElwain and partner Glenn E. McCormick for a reported sale price of $69,000 on March 1, 1944. At the time of the sale, it was still the only commercial radio station with Salem as its community of license.<ref name=\"bc44\"/> In May 1959, KSLM increased its daytime signal power to 5,000 watts and switched its network affiliation from Mutual to [[ABC News Radio|ABC]].<ref name=\"bc60\">{{cite book |title=1960 Broadcasting Yearbook |year=1960 |page=A-214 |chapter=Directory of AM and FM Radio stations in the U.S. |publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n===New ownership===\nAfter more than four decades of continuous corporate ownership, Oregon Radio, Inc., sold KSLM to Holiday Radio, Inc., in October 1977 as part of a two-station deal valued at $684,000.<ref name=\"bc79\">{{cite book |title=Broadcasting Yearbook 1979 |year=1979 |pages=C182-C183 |chapter=Directory of Radio Stations in the United States and Canada |publisher=Broadcasting Publications, Inc |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> The new ownership initially continued the [[middle of the road (music)|middle of the road]] music format that the station had been broadcasting for most of the 1970s.<ref name=\"bc79\"/> KSLM flipped to an [[adult contemporary]] music format in 1982.\n\nIn October 1985, Holiday Radio, Inc., reached an agreement to sell the station along with its FM sister station to Ronette Communications Corporation  for {{nowrap|$1.2 million}}. The deal was approved by the FCC on December 6 and the transaction was consummated on February 20, 1986.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19851008ET) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=82434 |date=February 20, 1986}}</ref> As part of an internal corporate reorganization, Ronette Communications Corporation applied to the FCC to transfer the KSLM broadcast license to Ronette Communications of Oregon, Inc., in February 1986. The transfer was approved by the FCC on February 11, 1986 and consummated on July 17, 1986.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19860206EG) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=85604 |date=July 17, 1986}}</ref> In mid-1986 the station transitioned to an [[oldies music]] format.\n\nJust over two years later, in March 1988, Daytona Group of Oregon, Inc., contracted to sell the station to John E. Grant's 1010 Broadcasting, Inc., for $215,000.<ref name=\"orh\"/> The deal was approved by the FCC on July 15, 1988 and consummated on July 26, 1988.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19880324EE) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=110610 |date=July 26, 1988}}</ref> 1010 Broadcasting, Inc., agreed in February 1992 to sell the station to K-Salem Communications (Greg Fabos, owner) for $151,000.<ref name=\"orh\"/> The deal was approved by the FCC on April 6, 1992 and consummated on May 8, 1992.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19920226ED) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=171019 |date=May 8, 1992}}</ref> The station began replacing live and local [[disc jockey]]s with programming from [[Satellite Music Network]]'s \"[[Kool Gold]]\" oldies format in February 1994.<ref name=\"orh\"/>\n\n===Trouble ahead===\nIn July 1994, K-Salem Communications reached an agreement to sell KSLM to Willamette Broadcasting Corp., Inc.  The deal was approved by the FCC on November 2, 1994 and consummated on December 22, 1994.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19940715EB) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=200980 |date=December 22, 1994}}</ref> The new owners had difficulty finding a new transmitter site for the station after the sale and the station was off the air from late 1995 until early 1997.<ref name=\"orh\"/>\n\nWith the station back in operation, Willamette Broadcasting Corp., Inc., announced in September 1998 that it would sell it to [[Entercom Communications]] subsidiary Entercom Portland License, LLC, for $605,000.<ref>{{cite news |work=Broadcasting & Cable |title=Changing Hands |first=Alisa |last=Holmes |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53123288.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025041314/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-53123288.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 25, 2012 |date=October 19, 1998 |quote=KSLM(AM) Salem, Ore. Price: $605000. Buyer: Entercom Portland License LLC, Bala Cynwyd, Pa. (David J. Field, president)}}</ref><ref name=\"epr1\">{{cite pressrelease |first=Tom |last=Baker |publisher=Entercom Portland |title=Entercom Announces Purchase of Salem, Oregon Station |url=http://www.entercom.com/newsPage.php?id=18 |date=September 4, 1998}}</ref> The deal was approved by the FCC on October 22, 1998 and consummated on December 14, 1998.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BAL-19980903EF) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=273557 |date=December 14, 1998}}</ref>\n\n===Changing callsigns===\nThe station took on a [[sports radio|sports talk]] format as a simulcast of [[Vancouver, Washington]], sister station KFXX (910 AM, now [[KMTT]]), branded as \"The Fan\", just after the sale to Entercom was completed.<ref name=\"epr1\"/>  When 910 AM became oldies-formatted KKSN, KSLM maintained the simulcast and became an oldies station. In January 2007, Entercom dropped KKSN's oldies format for [[talk radio]] as part of a pending sale to [[Salem Communications]] and KSLM began once again simulcasting sports radio [[KFXX (AM)|KFXX]], now at 1080 AM.<ref name=\"fyb\">{{cite web |publisher=Tower Site of the Week |title=The Big Trip 2006, Part III: Corvallis and Salem, OR |first=Scott |last=Fybush |url=http://www.fybush.com/sites/2007/site-070223.html |date=February 23, 2007 |quote=A quick note on KSLM: a few months after our visit, it took the KKSN calls when Entercom turned off the oldies and sold the 910 facility to Salem - the broadcaster, not the city. What's now KKSN 1390 in Salem now relays Entercom's Portland sports station, KFXX 1080.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=[[Statesman Journal]] |title=KKSN 910 sold - changes format |first=Michelle |last=Theriault |url=http://finndxer.wordpress.com/2007/02/20/kksn-910-sold-changes-format/ |date=February 20, 2007}}</ref> After more than 70 years as KSLM, Entercom applied for new call letters for this station in early 2007.  The FCC changed the callsign to '''KKSN''', the call letters of its former sister station and simulcast partner, on February 12, 2007.<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>  To better align it with Portland sister station [[KFXX (AM)|KFXX]] (1080 AM), the callsign was changed again on January 20, 2009, this time to '''KVXX'''.<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>\n\nOn May 1, 2009, KVXX dropped its simulcast of KFXX to begin airing [[Spanish language]] [[ESPN Deportes]] programming in conjunction with [[sister station]] KTRO.<ref name=\"ruf\"/><ref name=\"edr7\"/> The station was assigned the '''KWOD''' [[call sign]] by the FCC on May 29, 2009, after an Entercom-owned station in [[Sacramento, California]], switched to [[KUDL|KBZC]].<ref name=\"fcc1\"/>\n\nOn July 12, 2010, KWOD changed their format to [[English language]] sports, simulcasting [[sister station]] [[KFXX (AM)|KFXX]] (1080 AM, \"1080, The Fan\").\n\nOn March 31, 2014, KWOD changed their call letters to KZZD and changed format to regional Mexican. The change of call sign and format was coincident with Entercom's donation of KZZD's license to the Minority Media and Telecommunications Council, Inc. (MMTC). MMTC, in turn, sold the station to Edward Distell for a purchase price of $75,249; this transaction was consummated on June 20, 2014.\n\nOn September 23, 2016, KZZD changed their call letters to KZGD.\n\n==Former on-air staff==\n[[Peter Courtney]], a member of the [[Oregon Senate]], and since 2003 the President of the Senate, was once employed by KSLM as a [[pundit (expert)|political commentator]].<ref>{{cite web |work=Oregon Blue Book |title=Members of the Oregon Senate |url=https://sos.oregon.gov/blue-book/Pages/state/legislative/senate-images.aspx |accessdate=March 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|KZGD}}\n*{{FMQ|K228FN}}\n*{{FXL|K228FN}}\n*[http://photos.salemhistory.net/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=/sj&CISOPTR=289&CISOBOX=1&REC=6 Photo of station owners Bruce Kerr and Lou McCormick Paulus in front of the KSLM building in 1976]\n*[https://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=44578&.pdf FCC History Cards for KZGD]\n\n{{Spanish Radio Stations in Oregon}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Oregon|ZGD]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language radio stations in Oregon|ZGD]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1934]]\n[[Category:Media in Salem, Oregon]]\n[[Category:1934 establishments in Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Stereorock", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe beginning", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KZGD"}
{"title_page": "Frederic Leighton", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name          = The Lord Leighton\n| honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PRA}}\n| image         = 1880 Frederic Leighton - Self portrait.jpg\n| caption       = Frederic Leighton, \"Self-portrait\", 1880\n| birth_name    = Frederic Leighton \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1830|12|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1896|1|25|1830|12|3}}\n| death_place   = [[Kensington]], [[London]]\n| movement      = [[Academic art|Academicism]], [[Pre-Raphealite]] and British [[Aestheticism]]\n| awards        = [[Prix de Rome]], [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n| field         = Painting and sculpture\n| training      = [[Eduard von Steinle]] and [[Giovanni Costa]]\n| works         = ''[[Flaming June]]''\n}}\n\n'''Frederic Leighton, 1st Baron Leighton''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PRA}} (3 December 1830 \u2013 25 January 1896), known as '''Sir Frederic Leighton''' between 1878 and 1896, was a British painter, draughtsman and sculptor. His works depicted historical, [[biblical]], and [[classical antiquity|classical]] subject matter in an [[Academic art|academic style]].  His paintings were enormously popular, and expensive, during his lifetime, but fell out of critical favour for many decades in the early 20th century.  \n\nLeighton was the bearer of the shortest-lived [[peerage]] in history; after only one day his hereditary peerage became extinct upon his death.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/reppeers/peerrecords.htm Peerage records] \u2013 Leigh Rayment's Peerage Page</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[Image:Flaming June, by Frederic Lord Leighton (1830-1896).jpg|left|thumb|''[[Flaming June]]'' (1895; [[Museo de Arte de Ponce]]).]]\n[[File:Lord Leighton, Frederic, After Vespers, 1871.jpg|thumb|''After Vespers'' (1871; [[Princeton University Art Museum]])]]\n\nLeighton was born in [[Scarborough, England|Scarborough]] to Augusta Susan and Dr. Frederic Septimus Leighton. He had two sisters including [[Alexandra Orr|Alexandra]] who was [[Robert Browning]]'s biographer.<ref>\nElizabeth Lee, \u2018Orr, Alexandra (1828\u20131903)\u2019, rev. Katharine Chubbuck, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/35332, accessed 30 April 2017]</ref> He was educated at [[University College School]], London. He then received his artistic training on the European continent, first from [[Eduard von Steinle]] and then from [[Giovanni Costa]]. At age 17, in the summer of 1847, he met the philosopher [[Arthur Schopenhauer]] in Frankfurt and drew his portrait, in graphite and gouache on paper \u2014 the only known full-length study of Schopenhauer done from life.<ref>Crowther, Paul, and Miruna Cuzman. \"A Rediscovered Contemporary Full-Length Sketch-Portrait of Schopenhauer by Frederic, Lord Leighton.\" Schopenhauer Jahrbuch, 92 Band, Konigshausen und Neumann, 2011: 301\u2013306.</ref> When he was 24 he was in [[Florence]]; he studied at the [[Accademia di Belle Arti di Firenze|Accademia di Belle Arti]], and painted the procession of the [[Cimabue]] Madonna through the Borgo Allegri. From 1855 to 1859 he lived in Paris, where he met [[Jean Auguste Dominique Ingres|Ingres]], [[Eug\u00e8ne Delacroix|Delacroix]], [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot|Corot]] and [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Millet|Millet]].\n\nIn 1860, he moved to London, where he associated with the [[Pre-Raphaelite]]s. He designed [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]]'s tomb for [[Robert Browning]] in the [[English Cemetery, Florence]] in 1861. In 1864 he became an associate of the [[Royal Academy]] and in 1878 he became its President (1878\u201396).  His 1877 sculpture, ''[[Athlete Wrestling with a Python]]'', was considered at its time to inaugurate a renaissance in contemporary British sculpture, referred to as the [[New Sculpture]]. American art critic [[Earl Shinn]] claimed at the time that \"Except Leighton, there is scarce any one capable of putting up a correct frescoed figure in the archway of the Kensington Museum.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shinn|first1=Earl|title=The World's Art: From the International Exhibition|date=1880|publisher=Lovering|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=S6tBAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> His paintings represented Britain at the great [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|1900 Paris Exhibition]].\n\nLeighton was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] at [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]] in 1878,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=24651 |date=29 November 1878 |page=6695}}</ref> and was created a baronet, of Holland Park Road in the Parish of [[St Mary Abbots]], Kensington, in the County of Middlesex, eight years later.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25551 |date=22 January 1886 |page=328 }}</ref> He was the first painter to be given a [[peerage]], in the [[1896 New Year Honours]]. The patent creating him '''Baron Leighton''', of [[Church Stretton|Stretton]] in the County of Shropshire, was issued on 24 January 1896;<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26705 |date=31 January 1896 |page=587 }}</ref> Leighton died the next day of [[angina pectoris]].\n[[Image:Frederic Leighton - Cimabue's Madonna Carried in Procession - Google Art Project 2.jpg|thumb|''[[Cimabue's Celebrated Madonna]] is carried in Procession through the Streets of Florence'', 1853\u20131855]]\n[[Image:1876 Frederic Leighton - Daphnephoria.jpg|thumb|''[[Daphnephoria]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1874\u20131876, [[Lady Lever Art Gallery]]]]\n\nLeighton remained a bachelor; rumors of him having an illegitimate child with one of his models, in addition to the supposition that Leighton may have been a homosexual, continue to be debated.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Emanuel Cooper, ''The Sexual Perspective: Homosexuality and Art in the Last 100 Years in the West'', 2005</ref> He certainly enjoyed an intense and romantically tinged relationship with the poet [[Henry William Greville]] whom he met in Florence in 1856.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' vol 33</ref> The older man showered Leighton in letters, but the romantic affection seems not to have been reciprocated. Enquiry is furthermore hindered by the fact that Leighton left no diaries and his letters are telling in their lack of reference to his personal circumstances. No definite primary evidence has yet come to light that effectively dispels the secrecy that Leighton built up around himself, although it is clear that he did court a circle of younger men around his artistic studio.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nOn his death his [[baron]]y was extinguished after existing for only a day; this is a record in the [[Peerage]]. His house in [[Holland Park]], London has been turned into a museum, the [[Leighton House Museum]]. It contains many of his drawings and paintings, as well as some of his former art collection including works by [[Old Masters]] and his contemporaries such as a painting dedicated to Leighton by [[Sir John Everett Millais]]. The house also features many of Leighton's inspirations, including his collection of Iznik tiles. Its centrepiece is the magnificent Arab Hall. The Hall is featured in issue ten of ''[[Cornucopia (magazine)|Cornucopia]]''.<ref>[http://www.cornucopia.net/highlights10full.html ''Cornucopia'' 10, Ingres and Lady Mary Montagu, Leighton House, yurts, the Lycians plus elegant eggplant]. Cornucopia.net. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref>\nA [[blue plaque]] commemorates Leighton at Leighton House Museum.<ref name='EngHet'>{{cite web| url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/discover/blue-plaques/search/leighton-frederick-lord-leighton-1830-1896|title=LEIGHTON, FREDERICK, LORD LEIGHTON (1830\u20131896)|publisher=English Heritage| accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Artists Rifles==\nLeighton was an enthusiastic volunteer soldier, enrolling with the first group to join the 38th Middlesex (Artists') Rifle Volunteer Corps (later to be known as the [[Artists Rifles]]) on 5 October 1860.\n[[File:Frederic Leighton, Baron Leighton by George Frederic Watts.jpg|thumb|''Sir Frederic Leighton'' by [[George Frederic Watts]] (1881)]]\n[[File:Sir Frederick Leighton.jpg|thumb|Sir Frederic Leighton, later in his career.]]\n\nHis qualities of leadership were immediately identified, and he was promoted to command a Company within a few months. On 6 January 1869 [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] Leighton was elected to command the Artists Rifles by a general meeting of the corps. In the same year he was promoted to major and in 1875 to [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]]. Leighton resigned as [[commanding officer]] in 1883.\nThe painter [[James Abbott McNeill Whistler|James Whistler]] famously described the then, Sir Frederic Leighton, the commanding officer of the Artists Rifles, as the: \u201cColonel of the Royal Academy and the President of the Artists Rifles \u2013 aye, and he paints a little!\"\nAt his funeral, on 3 February 1896, his coffin was carried into [[St Paul's Cathedral]], past a [[guard of honour]] formed by the Artists Rifles.<ref>Barry Gregory. A History of The Artists Rifles 1859\u20131947. Pen & Sword. 2006.</ref>\n\n==Honours ==\n\n* 1864 \u2013 Associate of the [[Royal Academy]]\n* 1868 \u2013 Royal Academy [[Academician]]\n* 1878 \u2013 President of the Royal Academy\n* 1878 \u2013 [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] Officer\n* 1878 \u2013 [[Knight Bachelor]]\n* 1886 \u2013 Created a baronet in the [[Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n* 1889 \u2013 Associate member of the [[Institut de France|Institute of France]]\n* 1896 \u2013 Created a baron in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Death of Brunelleschi'' (1852), oil on canvas\n* ''The Fisherman and the Siren'', c. 1856\u201358 (66.3 x 48.7&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[Cimabue's Celebrated Madonna]] is carried in Procession through the Streets of Florence'' (1853\u201355),<ref>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/cgi-bin/WebObjects.dll/CollectionPublisher.woa/wa/work?workNumber=L275 Frederic, Lord Leighton | Cimabue's Celebrated Madonna | L275 | The National Gallery, London]. Nationalgallery.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> oil on canvas.\n* ''The Discovery of Juliet Apparently Lifeless'' (c.1858)<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=8581&searchid=6933&tabview=image Tate Collection | Study for 'The Discovery of Juliet Apparently Lifeless']. Tate.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref>\n* ''The Villa Malta, Rome'' (1860s),<ref>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/cgi-bin/WebObjects.dll/CollectionPublisher.woa/wa/work?workNumber=L851 Frederic, Lord Leighton | The Villa Malta, Rome | L851 | The National Gallery, London]. Nationalgallery.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> oil on canvas\n* ''[[The Painter's Honeymoon]]'', c. 1864 (83.8 x 77.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Mother and Child'', c. 1865, (48.2 x 82&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Actaea, the Nymph of the Shore''  (1868),<ref>[http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/search/artwork_e.jsp?mkey=10042 Artwork Page: Actaea, the Nymph of the Shore] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040828195038/http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/search/artwork_e.jsp?mkey=10042 |date=28 August 2004 }}. Cybermuse.gallery.ca. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> oil on canvas, (57.2 x 102.2&nbsp;cm) [[National Gallery of Canada]], Ottawa.\n* ''Daedalus and Icarus'', c. 1869, (138.2 x 106.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Hercules Wrestling with Death for the Body of Alcestis'' (1869\u201371) (132.4 x 265.4&nbsp;cm)\n* ''After Vespers'' 1871, (111.5 x 71.5&nbsp;cm), [[Princeton University Art Museum]]\n* ''Greek Girls Picking up Pebbles by the Sea'', 1871 (84 x 129.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Teresina '' (circa 1874) [[Christchurch Art Gallery Te Puna o Waiwhetu]], [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n* ''Music Lesson'', c. 1877, (92.8 x 118.1&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[An Athlete Wrestling with a Python]]''  (1877),<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=8579&searchid=6933&tabview=image Tate Collection | An Athlete Wrestling with a Python by Frederic, Lord Leighton]. Tate.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> bronze sculpture\n* ''Nausicaa'', c. 1878 (145 x 67&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Winding the Skein'', c. 1878, (100.3 x 161.3&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Light of the Harem'', c. 1880, (152.4 x 83.8&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Idyll'', c. 1880\u201381\n* ''Wedded'', (c. 1881\u20131882) (145.4 x 81&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[Cymon and Iphigenia (painting)|Cymon and Iphigenia]]'' (1884) [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]]\n* ''[[Captive Andromache]]'', c. 1888 (197 x 406.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''The Bath of Psyche'', (c. 1889\u201390) (189.2 x 62.2&nbsp;cm) [[Tate Gallery]]\n* ''The Garden of the Hesperides'', c. 1892, (169 x 169&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[Flaming June]]'' (1895), oil on canvas, [[Museo de Arte de Ponce|Museo de Arte de Ponce, Puerto Rico]] (120.6 x 120.6&nbsp;cm)\n* ''The Parable of the Wise and Foolish Virgins (Fresco)''<ref>[http://www.newforestparishes.com/page8/page2/files/page2_1.jpg Newforestparishes.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703215310/http://www.newforestparishes.com/page8/page2/files/page2_1.jpg |date=3 July 2007 }}</ref>\n* ''The armlet''\n* ''Phoebe'' (55.88 x 60.96&nbsp;cm)\n* ''A Bather''\n* [[The Leighton Frescoes]], ''The Arts of Industry as Applied to War'' and ''The Arts of Industry as Applied to Peace''\n* ''Phoenicians Trading with the Early Britons on the Coast of Cornwall'', 1895. Mural at the Royal Exchange, London\n* ''The Return of Perspephone'' 1891, oil on canvas, [[Leeds Art Gallery]]<ref>[http://www.leedsartgallery.co.uk/gallery/listings/l0033.php Leeds Art Gallery, listings]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"154px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nImage:Lord Frederick Leighton FLL006.jpg|''[[Icarus]] and [[Daedalus]]'', c. 1869\n\nImage:Frederic Leighton - The Garden of the Hesperides.jpg|''The Garden of the [[Hesperides]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1892, [[Lady Lever Art Gallery]]\n\nImage:Frederic Lord Leighton-The Sluggard-Victoria and Albert Museum.jpg|''The Sluggard'', 1885\nImage:An athlete wrestling with a python, white marble sculpture by Frederic, Lord Leighton, 1888-1891, private collection.jpg|''[[Athlete wrestling with a Python]]'', white marble sculpture, 1888\u20131891 (Private collection: on loan to the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]])\nImage:Leighton-The Fisherman and the Syren-c. 1856-1858.jpg|''The Fisherman and the Syren'', c.1856\u20131858, private collection\nImage:Leightonhero.jpg|''The Last Watch of [[Hero and Leander|Hero]]'', 1880\nFile:Frederic, Lord Leighton - Perseus and Andromeda - Google Art Project.jpg|[[Perseus and Andromeda (Leighton)|''Perseus and Andromeda'']], 1891, [[Walker Art Gallery]], Liverpool.\nFile:Leighton Moses views the Promised Land.jpg|''[[Moses]] views the Promised Land''\nImage:Leighton The Painter-s Honeymoon 1864.jpg|''[[The Painter's Honeymoon]]'', 1864\nFile:Frederick Leighton - Memories.jpg|''Memories'', 1883\nFile:1890s Frederick Leighton - Bath of Psyche.jpg|''The Bath of Psyche'', 1879\nImage:Frederick Leighton - Solitude.jpg|''Solitude'', c. 1890\n</gallery>\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"154px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Leighton, Frederic - Idyll - c. 1880-81.jpg|''Idyll'', c. 1880\u201381\nImage:Leighton Captive Andromache.jpg|''Captive [[Andromache]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1886\u20131888, [[Manchester City Art Gallery]]\nFile:Lord Frederic Leighton - Cymon and Iphigenia - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Iphigenia|Cymon and Iphigenia]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1884, [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]]\nFile:May Sartoris (about 15 years).jpg|Portrait of May Sartoris at about 15 years of age, [[Kimbell Art Museum]], Fort Worth, TX.\n</gallery><gallery widths=\"160\" heights=\"160\">\nFile:Frederick Leighton - Biondina.jpg|''Biondina'', 1879\n