er=[[John Everett Millais|Sir John Everett Millais, Bt]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Frederic Leighton}}\n{{Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leighton, Frederic Leighton, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1830 births]]\n[[Category:1896 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:English male sculptors]]\n[[Category:History painters]]\n[[Category:Members of The Club]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Prix de Rome for painting]]\n[[Category:People from Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n[[Category:People educated at University College School]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Artists' Rifles officers]]\n[[Category:Academic art]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Gold Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pour le M\u00e9rite (civil class)]]\n[[Category:Pre-Raphaelite painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:Orientalist painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:Members of the Athenaeum Club, London]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name          = The Lord Leighton\n| honorific_suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PRA}}\n| image         = 1880 Frederic Leighton - Self portrait.jpg\n| caption       = Frederic Leighton, \"Self-portrait\", 1880\n| birth_name    = Frederic Leighton \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1830|12|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Riding of Yorkshire]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|df=yes|1896|1|25|1830|12|3}}\n| death_place   = [[Kensington]], [[London]]\n| movement      = [[Academic art|Academicism]], [[Pre-Raphealite]] and British [[Aestheticism]]\n| awards        = [[Prix de Rome]], [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n| field         = Painting and sculpture\n| training      = [[Eduard von Steinle]] and [[Giovanni Costa]]\n| works         = ''[[Flaming June]]''\n}}\n\n'''Frederic Leighton, 1st Baron Leighton''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PRA}} (3 December 1830 \u2013 25 January 1896), known as '''Sir Frederic Leighton''' between 1878 and 1896, was a British painter, draughtsman and sculptor. His works depicted historical, [[biblical]], and [[classical antiquity|classical]] subject matter in an [[Academic art|academic style]].  His paintings were enormously popular, and expensive, during his lifetime, but fell out of critical favour for many decades in the early 20th century.  \n\nLeighton was the bearer of the shortest-lived [[peerage]] in history; after only one day his hereditary peerage became extinct upon his death.<ref>[http://www.leighrayment.com/reppeers/peerrecords.htm Peerage records] \u2013 Leigh Rayment's Peerage Page</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n[[Image:Flaming June, by Frederic Lord Leighton (1830-1896).jpg|left|thumb|''[[Flaming June]]'' (1895; [[Museo de Arte de Ponce]]).]]\n[[File:Lord Leighton, Frederic, After Vespers, 1871.jpg|thumb|''After Vespers'' (1871; [[Princeton University Art Museum]])]]\n\nLeighton was born in [[Scarborough, England|Scarborough]] to Augusta Susan and Dr. Frederic Septimus Leighton. He had two sisters including [[Alexandra Orr|Alexandra]] who was [[Robert Browning]]'s biographer.<ref>\nElizabeth Lee, \u2018Orr, Alexandra (1828\u20131903)\u2019, rev. Katharine Chubbuck, Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/35332, accessed 30 April 2017]</ref> He was educated at [[University College School]], London. He then received his artistic training on the European continent, first from [[Eduard von Steinle]] and then from [[Giovanni Costa]]. At age 17, in the summer of 1847, he met the philosopher [[Arthur Schopenhauer]] in Frankfurt and drew his portrait, in graphite and gouache on paper \u2014 the only known full-length study of Schopenhauer done from life.<ref>Crowther, Paul, and Miruna Cuzman. \"A Rediscovered Contemporary Full-Length Sketch-Portrait of Schopenhauer by Frederic, Lord Leighton.\" Schopenhauer Jahrbuch, 92 Band, Konigshausen und Neumann, 2011: 301\u2013306.</ref> When he was 24 he was in [[Florence]]; he studied at the [[Accademia di Belle Arti di Firenze|Accademia di Belle Arti]], and painted the procession of the [[Cimabue]] Madonna through the Borgo Allegri. From 1855 to 1859 he lived in Paris, where he met [[Jean Auguste Dominique Ingres|Ingres]], [[Eug\u00e8ne Delacroix|Delacroix]], [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot|Corot]] and [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Millet|Millet]].\n\nIn 1860, he moved to London, where he associated with the [[Pre-Raphaelite]]s. He designed [[Elizabeth Barrett Browning]]'s tomb for [[Robert Browning]] in the [[English Cemetery, Florence]] in 1861. In 1864 he became an associate of the [[Royal Academy]] and in 1878 he became its President (1878\u201396).  His 1877 sculpture, ''[[Athlete Wrestling with a Python]]'', was considered at its time to inaugurate a renaissance in contemporary British sculpture, referred to as the [[New Sculpture]]. American art critic [[Earl Shinn]] claimed at the time that \"Except Leighton, there is scarce any one capable of putting up a correct frescoed figure in the archway of the Kensington Museum.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Shinn|first1=Earl|title=The World's Art: From the International Exhibition|date=1880|publisher=Lovering|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=S6tBAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> His paintings represented Britain at the great [[Exposition Universelle (1900)|1900 Paris Exhibition]].\n\nLeighton was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] at [[Windsor, Berkshire|Windsor]] in 1878,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=24651 |date=29 November 1878 |page=6695}}</ref> and was created a baronet, of Holland Park Road in the Parish of [[St Mary Abbots]], Kensington, in the County of Middlesex, eight years later.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=25551 |date=22 January 1886 |page=328 }}</ref> He was the first painter to be given a [[peerage]], in the [[1896 New Year Honours]]. The patent creating him '''Baron Leighton''', of [[Church Stretton|Stretton]] in the County of Shropshire, was issued on 24 January 1896;<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26705 |date=31 January 1896 |page=587 }}</ref> Leighton died the next day of [[angina pectoris]].\n[[Image:Frederic Leighton - Cimabue's Madonna Carried in Procession - Google Art Project 2.jpg|thumb|''[[Cimabue's Celebrated Madonna]] is carried in Procession through the Streets of Florence'', 1853\u20131855]]\n[[Image:1876 Frederic Leighton - Daphnephoria.jpg|thumb|''[[Daphnephoria]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1874\u20131876, [[Lady Lever Art Gallery]]]]\n\nLeighton remained a bachelor; rumors of him having an illegitimate child with one of his models, in addition to the supposition that Leighton may have been a homosexual, continue to be debated.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Emanuel Cooper, ''The Sexual Perspective: Homosexuality and Art in the Last 100 Years in the West'', 2005</ref> He certainly enjoyed an intense and romantically tinged relationship with the poet [[Henry William Greville]] whom he met in Florence in 1856.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' vol 33</ref> The older man showered Leighton in letters, but the romantic affection seems not to have been reciprocated. Enquiry is furthermore hindered by the fact that Leighton left no diaries and his letters are telling in their lack of reference to his personal circumstances. No definite primary evidence has yet come to light that effectively dispels the secrecy that Leighton built up around himself, although it is clear that he did court a circle of younger men around his artistic studio.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nOn his death his [[baron]]y was extinguished after existing for only a day; this is a record in the [[Peerage]]. His house in [[Holland Park]], London has been turned into a museum, the [[Leighton House Museum]]. It contains many of his drawings and paintings, as well as some of his former art collection including works by [[Old Masters]] and his contemporaries such as a painting dedicated to Leighton by [[Sir John Everett Millais]]. The house also features many of Leighton's inspirations, including his collection of Iznik tiles. Its centrepiece is the magnificent Arab Hall. The Hall is featured in issue ten of ''[[Cornucopia (magazine)|Cornucopia]]''.<ref>[http://www.cornucopia.net/highlights10full.html ''Cornucopia'' 10, Ingres and Lady Mary Montagu, Leighton House, yurts, the Lycians plus elegant eggplant]. Cornucopia.net. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref>\nA [[blue plaque]] commemorates Leighton at Leighton House Museum.<ref name='EngHet'>{{cite web| url=http://www.english-heritage.org.uk/discover/blue-plaques/search/leighton-frederick-lord-leighton-1830-1896|title=LEIGHTON, FREDERICK, LORD LEIGHTON (1830\u20131896)|publisher=English Heritage| accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Artists Rifles==\nLeighton was an enthusiastic volunteer soldier, enrolling with the first group to join the 38th Middlesex (Artists') Rifle Volunteer Corps (later to be known as the [[Artists Rifles]]) on 5 October 1860.\n[[File:Frederic Leighton, Baron Leighton by George Frederic Watts.jpg|thumb|''Sir Frederic Leighton'' by [[George Frederic Watts]] (1881)]]\n[[File:Sir Frederick Leighton.jpg|thumb|Sir Frederic Leighton, later in his career.]]\n\nHis qualities of leadership were immediately identified, and he was promoted to command a Company within a few months. On 6 January 1869 [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] Leighton was elected to command the Artists Rifles by a general meeting of the corps. In the same year he was promoted to major and in 1875 to [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]]. Leighton resigned as [[commanding officer]] in 1883.\nThe painter [[James Abbott McNeill Whistler|James Whistler]] famously described the then, Sir Frederic Leighton, the commanding officer of the Artists Rifles, as the: \u201cColonel of the Royal Academy and the President of the Artists Rifles \u2013 aye, and he paints a little!\"\nAt his funeral, on 3 February 1896, his coffin was carried into [[St Paul's Cathedral]], past a [[guard of honour]] formed by the Artists Rifles.<ref>Barry Gregory. A History of The Artists Rifles 1859\u20131947. Pen & Sword. 2006.</ref>\n\n==Honours ==\n\n* 1864 \u2013 Associate of the [[Royal Academy]]\n* 1868 \u2013 Royal Academy [[Academician]]\n* 1878 \u2013 President of the Royal Academy\n* 1878 \u2013 [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] Officer\n* 1878 \u2013 [[Knight Bachelor]]\n* 1886 \u2013 Created a baronet in the [[Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n* 1889 \u2013 Associate member of the [[Institut de France|Institute of France]]\n* 1896 \u2013 Created a baron in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Death of Brunelleschi'' (1852), oil on canvas\n* ''The Fisherman and the Siren'', c. 1856\u201358 (66.3 x 48.7&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[Cimabue's Celebrated Madonna]] is carried in Procession through the Streets of Florence'' (1853\u201355),<ref>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/cgi-bin/WebObjects.dll/CollectionPublisher.woa/wa/work?workNumber=L275 Frederic, Lord Leighton | Cimabue's Celebrated Madonna | L275 | The National Gallery, London]. Nationalgallery.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> oil on canvas.\n* ''The Discovery of Juliet Apparently Lifeless'' (c.1858)<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=8581&searchid=6933&tabview=image Tate Collection | Study for 'The Discovery of Juliet Apparently Lifeless']. Tate.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref>\n* ''The Villa Malta, Rome'' (1860s),<ref>[http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/cgi-bin/WebObjects.dll/CollectionPublisher.woa/wa/work?workNumber=L851 Frederic, Lord Leighton | The Villa Malta, Rome | L851 | The National Gallery, London]. Nationalgallery.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> oil on canvas\n* ''[[The Painter's Honeymoon]]'', c. 1864 (83.8 x 77.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Mother and Child'', c. 1865, (48.2 x 82&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Actaea, the Nymph of the Shore''  (1868),<ref>[http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/search/artwork_e.jsp?mkey=10042 Artwork Page: Actaea, the Nymph of the Shore] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040828195038/http://cybermuse.gallery.ca/cybermuse/search/artwork_e.jsp?mkey=10042 |date=28 August 2004 }}. Cybermuse.gallery.ca. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> oil on canvas, (57.2 x 102.2&nbsp;cm) [[National Gallery of Canada]], Ottawa.\n* ''Daedalus and Icarus'', c. 1869, (138.2 x 106.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Hercules Wrestling with Death for the Body of Alcestis'' (1869\u201371) (132.4 x 265.4&nbsp;cm)\n* ''After Vespers'' 1871, (111.5 x 71.5&nbsp;cm), [[Princeton University Art Museum]]\n* ''Greek Girls Picking up Pebbles by the Sea'', 1871 (84 x 129.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Teresina '' (circa 1874) [[Christchurch Art Gallery Te Puna o Waiwhetu]], [[Christchurch]], New Zealand\n* ''Music Lesson'', c. 1877, (92.8 x 118.1&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[An Athlete Wrestling with a Python]]''  (1877),<ref>[http://www.tate.org.uk/servlet/ViewWork?cgroupid=999999961&workid=8579&searchid=6933&tabview=image Tate Collection | An Athlete Wrestling with a Python by Frederic, Lord Leighton]. Tate.org.uk. Retrieved on 20 February 2011.</ref> bronze sculpture\n* ''Nausicaa'', c. 1878 (145 x 67&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Winding the Skein'', c. 1878, (100.3 x 161.3&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Light of the Harem'', c. 1880, (152.4 x 83.8&nbsp;cm)\n* ''Idyll'', c. 1880\u201381\n* ''Wedded'', (c. 1881\u20131882) (145.4 x 81&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[Cymon and Iphigenia (painting)|Cymon and Iphigenia]]'' (1884) [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]]\n* ''[[Captive Andromache]]'', c. 1888 (197 x 406.5&nbsp;cm)\n* ''The Bath of Psyche'', (c. 1889\u201390) (189.2 x 62.2&nbsp;cm) [[Tate Gallery]]\n* ''The Garden of the Hesperides'', c. 1892, (169 x 169&nbsp;cm)\n* ''[[Flaming June]]'' (1895), oil on canvas, [[Museo de Arte de Ponce|Museo de Arte de Ponce, Puerto Rico]] (120.6 x 120.6&nbsp;cm)\n* ''The Parable of the Wise and Foolish Virgins (Fresco)''<ref>[http://www.newforestparishes.com/page8/page2/files/page2_1.jpg Newforestparishes.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703215310/http://www.newforestparishes.com/page8/page2/files/page2_1.jpg |date=3 July 2007 }}</ref>\n* ''The armlet''\n* ''Phoebe'' (55.88 x 60.96&nbsp;cm)\n* ''A Bather''\n* [[The Leighton Frescoes]], ''The Arts of Industry as Applied to War'' and ''The Arts of Industry as Applied to Peace''\n* ''Phoenicians Trading with the Early Britons on the Coast of Cornwall'', 1895. Mural at the Royal Exchange, London\n* ''The Return of Perspephone'' 1891, oil on canvas, [[Leeds Art Gallery]]<ref>[http://www.leedsartgallery.co.uk/gallery/listings/l0033.php Leeds Art Gallery, listings]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"154px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nImage:Lord Frederick Leighton FLL006.jpg|''[[Icarus]] and [[Daedalus]]'', c. 1869\n\nImage:Frederic Leighton - The Garden of the Hesperides.jpg|''The Garden of the [[Hesperides]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1892, [[Lady Lever Art Gallery]]\n\nImage:Frederic Lord Leighton-The Sluggard-Victoria and Albert Museum.jpg|''The Sluggard'', 1885\nImage:An athlete wrestling with a python, white marble sculpture by Frederic, Lord Leighton, 1888-1891, private collection.jpg|''[[Athlete wrestling with a Python]]'', white marble sculpture, 1888\u20131891 (Private collection: on loan to the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]])\nImage:Leighton-The Fisherman and the Syren-c. 1856-1858.jpg|''The Fisherman and the Syren'', c.1856\u20131858, private collection\nImage:Leightonhero.jpg|''The Last Watch of [[Hero and Leander|Hero]]'', 1880\nFile:Frederic, Lord Leighton - Perseus and Andromeda - Google Art Project.jpg|[[Perseus and Andromeda (Leighton)|''Perseus and Andromeda'']], 1891, [[Walker Art Gallery]], Liverpool.\nFile:Leighton Moses views the Promised Land.jpg|''[[Moses]] views the Promised Land''\nImage:Leighton The Painter-s Honeymoon 1864.jpg|''[[The Painter's Honeymoon]]'', 1864\nFile:Frederick Leighton - Memories.jpg|''Memories'', 1883\nFile:1890s Frederick Leighton - Bath of Psyche.jpg|''The Bath of Psyche'', 1879\nImage:Frederick Leighton - Solitude.jpg|''Solitude'', c. 1890\n</gallery>\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"154px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Leighton, Frederic - Idyll - c. 1880-81.jpg|''Idyll'', c. 1880\u201381\nImage:Leighton Captive Andromache.jpg|''Captive [[Andromache]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1886\u20131888, [[Manchester City Art Gallery]]\nFile:Lord Frederic Leighton - Cymon and Iphigenia - Google Art Project.jpg|''[[Iphigenia|Cymon and Iphigenia]]'', oil on canvas painting, 1884, [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]]\nFile:May Sartoris (about 15 years).jpg|Portrait of May Sartoris at about 15 years of age, [[Kimbell Art Museum]], Fort Worth, TX.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{external media | width = 210px | align = right | headerimage=[[File:Leighton Athlete Wrestling with a Python 01 Tate Britain.jpg|210px]] | video1 = [http://smarthistory.khanacademy.org/leightons-an-athlete-wrestling-with-a-python.html Leighton's ''An Athlete Wrestling with a Python''], [[Smarthistory]]\n}}\n\n* [[List of Orientalist artists]]\n* [[Orientalism]]\n* ''[[Romola]]'' \u2013 the novel by [[George Eliot]] for which he did the illustrations\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{EB1911|wstitle=Leighton, Frederick Leighton, Baron|volume=17|pages=396\u2013398}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Frederic Leighton}}\n* [http://www.frederic-leighton.org Frederic-Leighton.org] 114 works by Frederic Leighton\n* [http://www.artrenewal.org/pages/artist.php?artistid=14 Advice to Young Artists by Frederick Lord Leighton] high resolution images\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060617220548/http://www.lordfredericleighton.co.uk/ Scarborough, Birthplace of Lord Frederic Leighton]\n* [http://www.rbkc.gov.uk/subsites/museums/leightonhousemuseum.aspx Leighton House Museum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20031019204716/http://www.victorianartinbritain.co.uk/obituary/leighton.htm Obituary from ''The Times'']\n* [http://www.museumsyndicate.com/artist.php?artist=437 Leighton Gallery at MuseumSyndicate]\n*{{Art UK bio}} \n*[https://exchange.umma.umich.edu/resources/14186 Portrait of Sir Frederick Leighton, PRA] by [[Alphonse Legros]] at [[University of Michigan Museum of Art]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Francis Grant (artist)|Sir Francis Grant]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Royal Academy#Presidents (P.R.A.)|President of the Royal Academy]] |years=1878\u20131896}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Everett Millais|Sir John Everett Millais, Bt]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Frederic Leighton}}\n{{Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood|state=expanded}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leighton, Frederic Leighton, 1st Baron}}\n[[Category:1830 births]]\n[[Category:1896 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baronets in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:English male sculptors]]\n[[Category:History painters]]\n[[Category:Members of The Club]]\n[[Category:People of the Victorian era]]\n[[Category:Prix de Rome for painting]]\n[[Category:People from Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n[[Category:People educated at University College School]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Artists' Rifles officers]]\n[[Category:Academic art]]\n[[Category:Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Gold Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Pour le M\u00e9rite (civil class)]]\n[[Category:Pre-Raphaelite painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century British sculptors]]\n[