{"title_page": "Toni Collette", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian actress}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Toni Collette\n| image              = Toni Collette (48707296653) (cropped).jpg \n| alt                = Upper body shot of a 46-year-old woman. She has a slight smile. She wears her dark hair tied at the back and is in a white top with its collar up high. Behind her is advertising for the event, which is obscured.\n| caption            = Collette at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] premiere of ''[[Knives Out]]'' in September 2019\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1972|11|1}}<!-- full d.o.b. is verified by reliable sources in main text -->\n| birth_name         = Toni Collett<!-- Collett is her birth name, she added the final \"e\" for her stage name. Her first name is not Antonia. -->\n| birth_place        = Sydney, Australia\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| other_names        = Toni Collette-Galafassi\n| alma_mater         = {{hlist|[[National Institute of Dramatic Art]]|[[Australian Theatre for Young People]]}}\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Actress|musician}}\n| nationality        = Australian\n| years_active       = 1990\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Dave Galafassi|2003}}\n| children           = 2\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Toni Collette|Full List]]\n}}\n\n'''Toni Collette-Galafassi''' (born '''Toni Collett''';<!-- Her name is not Antonia. In 2015, she said: \"Wikipedia also claims my real name is Antonia, which is absolutely not true.\" She added the \"e\" to Collett, for her performance name, in her teens. --> 1 November 1972), credited professionally as '''Toni Collette''', is an Australian film, television, and stage actress and singer-songwriter. She is known for her work in [[independent films]] as well as support roles in studio films, for which she has received [[List of awards and nominations received by Toni Collette|accolades]]. Her feature film debut was in 1992 and her breakthrough was with the comedy-drama, ''[[Muriel's Wedding]]'' (1994), for which she earned a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe Award]] nomination. She achieved greater international recognition for her role in ''[[The Sixth Sense]]'' (1999) \u2013 the [[List of highest-grossing horror films|highest grossing horror movie]] at the time \u2013 for which she was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]].\n\nCollette's diverse film genres include period-drama [[The Hours (film)|''The Hours'']] (2002), drama ''[[Japanese Story]]'' (2003), comedy ''[[The Way, Way Back]]'' (2013), horror ''[[Hereditary (film)|Hereditary]]'' (2017) and mystery ''[[Knives Out (film)|Knives Out]]'' (2019). She received a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award]] nomination for her support role in ''[[About a Boy (film)|About a Boy]]'' (2002). Her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] performances include the lead role in ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'' (2000), which earned a nomination for a [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical|Tony Award]]. On TV she took the lead role in a comedy series, ''[[United States of Tara]]'' (2008\u201311), and won a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award]]. At the [[AACTA Awards]] she has won five statuettes from eight nominations.\n\nAs the lead singer of [[Toni Collette & the Finish]], she wrote all 11&nbsp;tracks of their sole album, ''Beautiful Awkward Pictures'' (October 2006). They toured Australia but have not performed nor released any new material after 2007. She co-owns a film production company, Vocab Films, with Jen Turner. In 2017 they bought the film rights for the novel and screenplay, ''[[The Best of Adam Sharp]]'' (2016). Collette married Dave Galafassi (drummer of [[Gelbison]]) in January 2003 and the couple have two children.\n\n== Early life ==\n\nToni Collett<ref>Although some sources state her full name as Antonia, Collette clarified in 2015 that \"Wikipedia also claims my real name is Antonia, which is absolutely not true\" {{cite journal | url = http://www.out.com/movies/2015/10/26/toni-collette-talks-skinny-dipping-gay-fandom | title = Toni, Collected | first = R. Kurt | last = Osenlund | date = 26 October 2015 | journal = [[Out (magazine)|Out]] | accessdate = 4 April 2020 }}</ref> was born on 1 November 1972, in [[Plumpton, New South Wales|Plumpton]], a suburb in Sydney, the eldest of three children.<ref name=\"SBS Who?\"/><ref name=\"Hume\"/>. Her father, Bob Collett, was a truck driver while her mother, Judy (''[[Given name|n\u00e9e]]'' Cook), was a customer-service representative.<ref name=\"SBS Who?\"/> She appeared on [[SBS (Australian TV_channel)|SBS TV]]'s ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (Australian TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'' in August 2015 for \"Season 7 Episode 2: Toni Collette\", to find out more about her grandparents.<ref name=\"SBS Who?\"/> Bob was possibly born as a result of his mother Norma (''[[Given name|n\u00e9e]]'' McWhinney) having an extra-marital affair with a [[Chief petty officer (United States)|US Navy Chief Petty Officer]] stationed in Australia during, and after, World War II.<ref name=\"SBS Who?\">{{cite web | url = https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/video/492916803932/who-do-you-think-you-are-toni-collette | title = Season 7 Episode 2: Toni Collette | work = [[Who Do You Think You Are? (Australian TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]] | publisher = [[SBS (Australian TV_channel)#SBS_On_Demand|SBS On Demand]] | date = 11 August 2015 | accessdate = 4 April 2020 }} Note: Only available in Australia. Login with email address required to access video, available for 41 days from 4 April 2020.</ref> Norma and her husband (Harold \"Stanley\" Collett)<ref name=\"Parry\">{{cite news | url = http://www.artemisfilms.com/_blog/Artemis_News/post/toni-collettes-family-secrets-unravel/ | title = Toni Collette's family secrets unravel | last = Parry | first = Jessica | publisher = Artemis Media | date = 21 July 2015 | access-date = 7 April 2020 }}</ref> were going through a divorce, and Bob's DNA test determined that Stanley was not his father.<ref name=\"SBS Who?\"/> Despite a public appeal in August 2015, her suspected biological grandfather's name is not known.<ref name=\"SBS Who?\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.universityfox.com/stories/man-reunites-with-birth-mother-51-years-after-she-held-him-for-six-hours/ | title = Man reunites with birth mother 51 years after she held him for just six hours | last = Wiltons | first = Rebbekah | date = 4 April 2019 | website = University Fox | access-date = 5 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nShe has described her family as, \"[not] the most communicative\" but that despite her parents' lack of money, they made them feel cared for and they were supportive.<ref name=\"McLean\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2002/apr/26/artsfeatures | title = Interview: Toni Collette | last = McLean | first = Gareth | date = 26 April 2002 | work = [[The Guardian]] | access-date = 5 January 2020 | issn = 0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news | url = https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/straight-to-the-top-20030927-gdhgvf.html | title = Straight to the top | date = 27 September 2003 | work = [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | access-date = 5 January 2020 }}</ref> She has fond memories of growing up in [[Blacktown]] where she joined Judy on Saturday afternoons watching movie matinees, presented by [[Bill Collins (television presenter)|Bill Collins]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news | url = https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/dont-call-her-muriel-20120903-2593l.html | title = Don't call her Muriel | date = 7 September 2012 | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | access-date = 5 January 2020 }}</ref> She described her younger self as having \"crazy\" amounts of confidence.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jun/10/toni-collette-hereditary-interview-i-dont-like-horror-films | title = Toni Collette: 'I don't like horror films \u2013 I'm too petrified' | last = Ellen | first = Barbara | date = 10 June 2018 | work = [[The Observer]] | access-date = 5 January 2020 | issn = 0029-7712 }}</ref> When she was 11 she believed she had [[appendicitis]] and convinced doctors: she was taken to an emergency department and had the appendix removed.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"Bhattacharya\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/aug/20/features.magazine | title = Sanjiv Bhattacharya meets Hollywood's leading lady Toni Collette : Film |  | last = Bhattacharya | first = Sanjiv | work = The Guardian | date = 20 August 2006 | access-date = 9 April 2020 }}</ref> As a student at [[Blacktown Girls High School]], her favourite activities included netball, tap-dancing and swimming.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{ cite news | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/10681592/Toni-Collette-interview-If-I-couldnt-work-Id-wither-and-die.html | title = Toni Collette interview: 'If I couldn't work, I'd wither and die' | last = Harrod | first = Horatia | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | date = 13 March 2014 | access-date = 5 January 2020  | issn = 0307-1235 }}</ref> She took part in local singing competitions.<ref name=\":1\"/> Her ambition was to perform in [[Musical theatre|musicals]] as she loved to sing and dance.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.ft.com/content/15f94540-7a09-11e6-97ae-647294649b28 | title = The Inventory: Australian actor Toni Collette | work = [[Financial Times]] | url-access = subscription | access-date = 5 January 2020 }}</ref>\n\nHer first acting role was a high school performance of ''[[Godspell]]'' at 14&nbsp;years old, which she auditioned for by singing Whitney Houston's \"[[Saving All My Love for You]]\".<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{cite journal | url = https://www.biography.com/actor/toni-collette | title = Toni Collette | work = [[Biography (TV program)|Biography]] | access-date = 5 January 2020 }}</ref> She decided to become an actor in the following year,<ref name=\"McLean\"/> and was influenced by [[Geoffrey Rush]]'s stage performance in ''[[The Diary of a Madman]]'' (July\u2013August 1989).<ref name=\"AusStage Rush\">{{cite web | url = https://ausstage.edu.au/pages/event/1875 | title = Event: ''The Diary of a Madman'' | publisher = [[AusStage]] | access-date = 9 April 2020 }}</ref> At age 16, with her parents' approval, she transferred to the [[Australian Theatre for Young People]] in 1989, and later explained, \"I was 16. And it's not like I wasn't good at school, or I didn't enjoy it, I did. I just loved acting more. I don't regret that decision, but I can't believe I made it.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> The actor returned an extra \"e\" at the end of her surname,<ref name=\"SBS Who?\"/> which Stanley Collett had removed,<ref name=\"Parry\"/> as it sounded better for a stage name. She started at [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] (NIDA) in early 1991; but left after 18&nbsp;months to appear as Sonya in ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'' (August\u2013September 1992), directed by [[Neil Armfield]], alongside Rush in the title role.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"AusStage List\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1990\u201399: Breakthrough and early roles===\n\n[[File:Nida dusk.jpg|alt=An outside, night-time shot of the building. It is well lit and has almost full-length glass panels. At the right side is the name of the drama school and also the lettering for Parade Theatres. An interior stairway is visible on the left side and a rounded wooden structure at right.|thumb|Collette studied acting at the [[National Institute of Dramatic Art]] (NIDA) in [[Kensington, New South Wales|Kensington]] in 1991\u201392.]]\nCollette made her TV debut in 1990, in a guest appearance, as Tracy, on the [[Seven Network]] drama series ''[[A Country Practice]]'' Season 10, Episode 31, \"The Sting: Part 1\".<ref name=\"Dishinger\">{{cite web | url= https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/pictures/the-sixth-sense-cast-then-and-now/haley-joel-osment-cole-sear/ | title = ''The Sixth Sense'' Cast: Then and Now  \u2013 Toni Collette, Lynn Sear | last = Dishinger | first = Lauren | work = [[US Weekly|US Magazine]] | date = 6 August 2019 | access-date = 5 April 2020 }}</ref> Her first professional theatre role was as Debbie in ''Operation Holy Mountain'' in May of that year at [[Penrith, New South Wales#Arts|Q Theatre, Penrith]].<ref name=\"AusStage List\">{{cite web | url = https://ausstage.edu.au/pages/contributor/226957 | title = Contributor: Toni Collette | publisher = AusStage | accessdate = 4 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite journal | author1 = Barnes, Frank | title = Theatre ''Operation Holy Mountain'' by David Holman Q Theatre Penrith, Director Helmut Bakaitis (16 May 1990) | journal = Education: Journal of the N.S.W. Public School Teachers Federation | publication-date = 16 May 1990 | volume = 71 | issue = 06 | page = 22 | issn = 0013-1156 }}</ref> Frank Barnes of ''Journal of the N.S.W Public School Teachers Federation'' noticed, \"Collette [is] simply amazing in her professional debut as the girl with cerebral palsy.\"<ref name=\"Barnes\"/> She joined the [[Sydney Theatre Company]] and, from December 1990 to February 1991, appeared in ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' at the [[Sydney Opera House#Performance venues and facilities|Drama Theatre, Sydney Opera House]].<ref name=\"AusStage List\"/> She performed [[Cordelia (King Lear)|Cordelia]] in ''[[King Lear]]'' (March 1994) and was also in stage productions at the [[Belvoir Street Theatre]], directed by Rush.<ref name=\"AusStage List\"/>\n\nIn 1992 she made her feature film debut as part of the ensemble comedy-drama [[Spotswood (film)|''Spotswood'']] (known in the US as ''The Efficiency Expert''), which starred [[Anthony Hopkins]] and included \"a then unheard-of\" [[Russell Crowe]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\">{{cite web | url = https://www.allmovie.com/artist/toni-collette-p14165 | title = Toni Collette {{!}} Biography, Movie Highlights and Photos | last = Flint Marx | first = Rebecca | publisher = [[AllMovie]] | accessdate = 5 April 2020 }} Note: this source incorrectly provides Antonia Collette as her alias. To access further information, click on a tab, e.g. Filmography or Awards. </ref> She played Wendy, a factory worker who harbours a secret attraction towards fellow worker Carey ([[Ben Mendelsohn]]).<ref name=\"Galvin\">{{cite news | url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article213877443 | title = ''Spotswood'' | newspaper = [[Filmnews]] | date = 1 December 1991 | access-date = 4 April 2020 | page = 16 |via = [[Trove]] ([[National Library of Australia]]) }}</ref> ''[[Filmnews]]''{{'}} Peter Galvin observed, \"it's here that the film finds real warmth, vigour, and pain, all contained in [her] expressive face; she's terrific and so is Mendelsohn simply because we believe them.\"<ref name=\"Galvin\"/> Andrew Urban of ''Urban Cinephile'' felt that, \"[she] has a lovely role and does it with minimalist excellence.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=13403&s=DVD | title = ''Spotswood'': DVD | last = Urban | first = Andrew L. | website = Urban Cinefile | access-date = 28 January 2020 }}</ref> For the performance, she earned her first [[AACTA Awards|AACTA Award]] nomination, for [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name=\"1991 Australian Film Institute Awards\">{{cite web | url = https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1991/ | title = The 33rd Australian Film Institute Awards (1991) Nominees and Winners | publisher = [[Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts]] (AACTA) | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181224171233/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1991/ | archivedate = 24 December 2018 | url-status = live | accessdate = 15 April 2020 }} Note: from 1958 to 2010 these awards were known as Australian Film Institute Awards or AFI Awards.</ref> Between auditions for roles, she worked part-time delivering pizzas and selling jeans.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite news | url = https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/toni-collette-some-people-stick-to-the-rules-some-question-them-20180918-p504gh.html | title = Toni Collette: 'Some people stick to the rules, some question them' | last = Kelly | first = Guy | date = 21 September 2018 | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | access-date = 18 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nDuring 1992 her agent alerted her to a proposed film project with a good role; a year later ''[[Muriel's Wedding]]'' (September 1994) was financed and started casting in June 1993.<ref>{{citation | title = ''Muriel's Wedding'' 25th Anniversary Celebration Q&A with Toni Collette | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eDw91-owWr8 | access-date = 28 January 2020 }}</ref> Although the actor auditioned on the first day, she did not win until three months later.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/16/arts/up-and-coming-toni-collette-and-rachel-griffiths-muriels-wedding-brings.html | title = Up and Coming: Toni Collette and Rachel Griffiths; ''Muriel's Wedding'' Brings Bliss to Two Young Actresses | last = Dargis | first = Manohla | date = 16 April 1995 | work = [[The New York Times]]| url-access = subscription | access-date = 28 January 2020 | issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref><ref name=\"Couch\"/> In preparation for portraying Muriel, the actor gained {{convert|18|kg|lbs}} in 7&nbsp;weeks.<ref name=\"Hume\">{{cite news|last=Hume|first=Marion|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/07/20/1090089151504.html|title=Free Spirit|date=21 July 2004|work=[[The Sun-Herald]]|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Couch\">{{cite journal | url = https://people.com/archive/let-her-eat-cake-vol-43-no-13/ | title = Let Her Eat Cake | last = Couch | first = Shelli-Anne | work = [[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date = 5 April 2020 }}</ref> The film was a critical and commercial success, grossing US$57.5&nbsp;million on a budget of US$9&nbsp;million. [[James Berardinelli]] of ''Reelviews'' called her \"vibrant and energetic,\" while Peter Stack of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' opined that Collette played the lead role with \"disarming earnestness.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.reelviews.net/reelviews/muriel-s-wedding | title = ''Muriel's Wedding'' | last = Berardinelli | first = James | authorlink = James Berardinelli | website = Reelviews Movie Reviews | access-date = 30 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Seeking-Bliss-Muriel-Finds-Herself-2990644.php | title = Seeking Bliss, 'Muriel' Finds Herself | last = Stack | first = Peter | date = 15 March 1996 | website = [[San Francisco Chronicle]] | access-date = 30 January 2020 }}</ref> She received her first [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] nomination, for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Best Actress]] and won an [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|AACTA Award for Best Actress]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"1994 Australian Film Institute Awards\">{{cite web | url = https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1994/ | title = The 36th Australian Film Institute Awards (1994) Nominees and Winners | publisher = Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181224171518/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1994/ | archivedate = 24 December 2018 | url-status = live | accessdate = 12 April 2020 }} Note: from 1958 to 2010 these awards were known as Australian Film Institute Awards or AFI Awards.</ref>\n\nIn 1996 she had parts in three critically acclaimed films. In the comedy-drama [[Cosi (film)|''Cos\u00ec'']], which reunited her with ''Muriel's Wedding'' castmate [[Rachel Griffiths]], she played an actor recovering from drug addiction. [[David Stratton]] of [[Variety (magazine)|''Variety'']] said Collette \"[gave] a terrific performance.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/cosi-1200445232/ | title = ''Cosi'' | last = Stratton | first = David | author-link = David Stratton | date = 26 March 1996 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | access-date = 30 January 2020 }}</ref> In the drama ''[[Lilian's Story]]'' she played an eccentric woman sent to a [[Lunatic asylum|mental asylum]] in her youth. Stratton found her to be \"poignant\" and took note of her range and depth.<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/lilian-s-story-1200445381/ | title = ''Lilian's Story'' | last = Stratton | first = David | date = 11 March 1996 | work = Variety | access-date = 30 January 2020 }}</ref> She won her second AACTA Award, this time for [[AACTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|Best Actress in a Supporting Role]].<ref name=\"1996 Australian Film Institute Awards\">{{cite web | url = https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1996-2/ | title = The 38th Australian Film Institute Awards (1996) Nominees and Winners | publisher = Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181224171653/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1996-2/ | archivedate = 24 December 2018 | url-status = live | accessdate = 15 April 2020 }} Note: from 1958 to 2010 these awards were known as Australian Film Institute Awards or AFI Awards.</ref> In the period comedy ''[[Emma (1996 theatrical film)|Emma]]'', an adaptation of Jane Austen's [[Emma (novel)|novel of the same name]], she played Harriet Smith, a close friend of the [[Emma Woodhouse|titular character]]. Originally dismissive of Austen's works, she found ''Emma'' to be \"warm and witty and clever.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web | url = https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Aussie-actress-shines-in-the-latest-Austen-outing-3131029.php | title = Aussie actress shines in the latest Austen outing | last = Ganahl | first = Jane | date = 4 August 1996 | website = SFGate | access-date = 30 January 2020 }}</ref> Jane Ganahl of ''San Francisco Chronicle'' wrote, \"[Harriet was] played with heartbreaking empathy... desperately trying to meet Mr. Right \u2013 so awkwardly you fear she'll slip on a banana peel.\"<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nShe starred alongside [[Lisa Kudrow]], [[Parker Posey]] and [[Alanna Ubach]] in ''[[Clockwatchers]]'' (1997) which depicted the lives of four friends working in an office. Dustin Putman of ''TheFilmFile'' called it a \"jewel of a film\" and praised the performances of the cast, particularly Collette whom he referred to as \"outstanding.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.themovieboy.com/reviews/c/97_clockwatchers.htm | title = Dustin's Review: ''Clockwatchers'' (1997) | last = Putman | first = Dustin | work = TheFilmFile | access-date = 30 January 2020 }}</ref> For her supporting role as Michelle in ''[[The Boys (1998 film)|The Boys]]'' (1998) she won her third [[AACTA Awards|AACTA Award]].<ref name=\"1998 Australian Film Institute Awards\">{{cite web | url = https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1998/ | title = The 40th Australian Film Institute Awards (1998) Nominees and Winners | publisher = Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181224172140/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/1990-1999/year/1998/ | archivedate = 24 December 2018 | url-status = live | accessdate = 15 April 2020 }} Note: from 1958 to 2010 these awards were known as Australian Film Institute Awards or AFI Awards.</ref> Although ''[[Velvet Goldmine]]'' (1998), returned less than half its production budget at the box office,<ref name=numbers>{{cite web | url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Velvet-Goldmine#tab=summary | title = ''Velvet Goldmine'' (1998) - Financial Information | work = [[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] | accessdate = 3 December 2016 }}</ref> [[Metacritic]] reports a 65% score based on 25 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/velvet-goldmine | title = ''Velvet Goldmine'' Reviews | work = [[Metacritic]] | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | accessdate = 3 December 2016}}</ref> It grew in stature after its release to become a [[cult film]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://encoremag.com/new-york/articles/282/glam-velvet-goldmine-mccarren | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20111004213320/http://encoremag.com/new-york/articles/282/glam-velvet-goldmine-mccarren | title = Glam's ''Velvet Goldmine'' Marks End of McCarren's Film Season | last = Fuller | first= Melynda | date = 1 August 2008 | work = encoremag.com | url-status = dead | archive-date = 4 October 2011 | access-date = 5 April 2020 }}</ref> Collette credited it with revitalising her passion for acting as it had freed her from distress she had been facing.<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web | url = http://www.urbancinefile.com.au/home/view.asp?a=2833&s=interviews | title = Urban Cinefile: Collette, Toni: ''Sixth Sense'' | last = Urban | first = Andrew L. | website = Urban Cinefile | access-date = 31 January 2020 }}</ref> Less well received was her next film, ''[[8\u00bd Women]]'' (1999): Metacritic gave it a \"generally unfavorable\" score of 36%.<ref>{{metacritic film|8-women-2000|{{frac|8|1|2}} Women}}</ref>\n\n===1999\u20132004: ''The Sixth Sense'' and Broadway===\n\nWhen Collette received [[M. Night Shyamalan]]'s script for ''[[The Sixth Sense]]'' (1999), she feared it would be a \"formulaic Hollywood action drama.\"<ref name=\":02\" /> However, she was moved by the story and agreed to audition, winning the role over other actors, including [[Marisa Tomei]].<ref name=\":02\" /> She portrayed Lynn Sear, a single mother struggling to raise her son Cole ([[Haley Joel Osment]]) who communicates with ghosts.<ref name=\":02\"/><ref name=\"Cormier\">{{cite journal | url = https://www.mentalfloss.com/article/66913/17-straightforward-facts-about-sixth-sense | title = 15 Twisted Facts About ''The Sixth Sense'' | last = Cormier | first = Roger | date = 6 August 2017 | work = [[Mental Floss]] | url-status  =live | accessdate = 6 April 2020 }}</ref> Gary Thompson of ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' observed, \"the scene in the car when [Cole] divulges his secret is so riveting... and it's so well-acted by Osment and Collette.\"<ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite news | url = https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/movies/sixth-sense-20th-anniversary-m-night-shyamalan-20190727.html | title = ''The Sixth Sense'' at 20: M. Night Shyamalan's breakout still stuns | last = Thompson | first = Gary | work = [[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] | date = 27 July 2019 | accessdate = 2 February 2020 }}</ref> He added, \"she'd become the greatest screen weeper of her generation.\"<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> ''The Sixth Sense'' grossed US$670&nbsp;million on a budget of US$40&nbsp;million and became the [[1999 in film|second-highest-grossing film of 1999]].<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/08/how-sixth-sense-conquered-hollywood-1999/595558/ | title = How ''The Sixth Sense'' Conquered Hollywood in 1999 | last = Sims | first = David | date = 6 August 2019 | work = [[The Atlantic]] | accessdate = 2 February 2020 }}</ref> It gathered six [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nominations including Collette's for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"Collis\"/> She reflected, \"There was some definite feeling we all had that it was going to somehow be special. [... It] did really well and has been loved by a lot of people.\"<ref name=\"Collis\">{{cite journal | url = https://ew.com/movies/2018/04/25/hereditary-sixth-sense-toni-collette/ | title = Toni Collette says making horror movie ''Hereditary'' reminded her of ''The Sixth Sense'' | last = Collis | first = Clark | work = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | date = 25 April 2018 | accessdate = 3 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:M. Night Shyamalan by Gage Skidmore.jpg|alt=A 45-year-old man is shown in a head shot. He is broadly smiling and is in front of a microphone.|thumb|233x233px|[[M. Night Shyamalan]] cast Collette in ''[[The Sixth Sense]]'' (1999), which extended her international recognition.]]\nIn 2000 she made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut with a leading role in [[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|''The Wild Party'']], playing Queenie, a masochistic [[showgirl]] who hosts a lavish party with her husband. Originally written for [[Vanessa Williams]], it went to Collette after the former was unavailable.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.talkinbroadway.com/cabaret/lachiusa.html | title = Cabaret Interview with Michael John LaChiusa | last = Frank | first = Jonathan | work = Talkin' Broadway | accessdate = 6 April 2020 }}</ref> [[Charles Isherwood]] felt under-whelmed by the musical and the actor's performance, \"[Collette's] Queenie is flat and one-dimensional; she doesn't convey the warmth that invites emotional investment.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2000/legit/reviews/the-wild-party-4-1200461750/| title = ''The Wild Party'' | last = Isherwood  |first = Charles | authorlink = Charles Isherwood | date = 14 April 2000 | work = Variety | accessdate = 3 February 2020 }}</ref> [[Ben Brantley]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' differed, \"Ms. Collette... gives the evening's most fully realized performance,\" but criticised the lack of chemistry with [[Yancey Arias]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/14/movies/theater-review-having-fun-yet-jazz-babies.html | title = Theater Review; Having Fun Yet, Jazz Babies? | last = Brantley | first = Ben | date = 14 April 2000 | work = The New York Times | url-access = subscription | accessdate = 3 February 2020 | issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> She was nominated for the [[Tony Award for Best Leading Actress in a Musical]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/> Collette turned down the title role in ''[[Bridget Jones's Diary (film)|Bridget Jones's Diary]]'' due to her Broadway commitments.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.filmink.com.au/close-casting-calls-toni-collette-in-bridget-joness-diary-2001/ | title = Close Casting Calls: Toni Collette in ''Bridget Jones's Diary'' (2001) | last = Free | first = Erin | date = 18 September 2016 | newspaper = [[Filmink|FilmInk]] | url-access = subscription | accessdate = 6 April 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nShe followed with a supporting role in the action thriller [[Shaft (2000 film)|''Shaft'']] (2000). The film received \"mixed or average reviews,\"<ref>{{metacritic film|shaft|Shaft}}</ref> and grossed US$107.2&nbsp;million on a budget of US$46&nbsp;million. Kam Williams of ''African American Literature Book Club'' noticed, \"Collette lends the film some convincing and welcome dramatic weight as the frightened, conflicted Diane.\"<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite web | url = https://aalbc.com/reviews/film-reviews.php?id=1743 | title = ''Shaft'' by Film Reviewed | last = Williams | first = Kam | work = [[AALBC.com|African American Literature Book Club]] | access-date = 7 April 2020 }}</ref> Whereas John Patterson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' rated it as a \"career low\" for her.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/> In 2001 she appeared in the [[HBO]] [[Television film|TV movie]] [[Dinner with Friends (film)|''Dinner with Friends'']] and played Beth, a middle-aged woman who struggles with her husband leaving her for another woman. Steven Oxman of ''Variety'' said that she was \"well suited\" to her role, while Bruce Fetts of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' praised her \"flawless\" American accent.<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2001/tv/reviews/dinner-with-friends-4-1200469558/ | title = ''Dinner with Friends'' | last = Oxman | first = Steven | date = 8 August 2001 | work = Variety | accessdate = 3 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = https://ew.com/article/2001/08/06/dinner-friends/ | title = ''Dinner with Friends'' | last = Fetts | first = Bruce | work = Entertainment Weekly | accessdate = 3 February 2020 }}</ref> The show earned a nomination for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/>\n\nIn 2002 she had a supporting role in [[The Hours (film)|''The Hours'']], based on the [[The Hours (novel)|novel of the same name]], playing Kitty, a woman who plans to undergo surgery for her [[infertility]]. John Patterson felt she gave an \"utterly convincing small-scale emotional meltdown born of suburban sadness and sexual self-repression.\"<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref name=\"Clifford\">{{cite web | url = https://www.reelingreviews.com/thehours.htm | title = ''The Hours'' | last1 = Clifford | first1 = Laura | last2 = Clifford | first2 = Robin | work = Reeling: The Movie Review Show | access-date = 4 February 2020 }}</ref> The film received positive reviews and was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/> In [[About a Boy (film)|''About a Boy'']] (2002) she portrayed a woman with [[Depression (mood)|depression]] who attempts to commit [[suicide]]. Daniel Saney of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' said that she was \"as impressive as ever\" while Sheila Johnston of ''[[Screen International|Screen Daily]]'' praised her \"powerful presence.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.digitalspy.com/movies/a30085/about-a-boy/ | title = ''About a Boy'' | last = Saney | first = Daniel | date = 7 March 2006 | website = [[Digital Spy]] | access-date = 4 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.screendaily.com/about-a-boy/408661.article | title = ''About a Boy'' | last = Johnston | first = Sheila | website = [[Screen International|Screen Daily]] | access-date = 4 February 2020 }}</ref> She was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role]] and won the [[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for both 2002 performances.<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/>\n\nCollette played the lead role in ''[[Japanese Story]]'' (2003) as Sandy  an Australian [[geologist]] who develops an intense relationship with a Japanese businessman. It was screened at the [[2003 Cannes Film Festival]]. The performance led to reviewers welcoming her return to lead roles: the first since ''Muriel's Wedding''. John Patterson wrote that she gave a \"shattering performance, masterfully controlled and detailed, and all the proof her fans ever needed of her special brilliance.\"<ref name=\"Patterson\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2004/jun/05/patterson.comment | title = On top down under | last = Patterson | first = John | date = 5 June 2004 | work = The Guardian | access-date = 7 April 2020 | issn = 0261-3077 }}</ref> Richard Porton of the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' remarked, \"[her] pitch-perfect performance and the stunning evocation of the forbidding and beautiful outback make this film unexpectedly rewarding.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/japanese-story/Film?oid=1151584 | title = ''Japanese Story'' | last = Porton | first = Richard M. | work = [[Chicago Reader]] | access-date = 4 February 2020 }}</ref> Critics praised her emotional range, with some regarding the performance to be the best of her career.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/j/japanese_story.html |title = Review: ''Japanese Story'' | website = Reelviews Movie Reviews | access-date = 4 February 2020 }}</ref> She won her fourth AACTA Award statuette for her portrayal of Sandy Edwards in ''Japanese Story''.<ref name=\"2003 Australian Film Institute Awards\">{{cite web | url = https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/2000-2010/year/2003/ | title = The 45th Australian Film Institute Awards (2003) Nominees and Winners | publisher = Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181224172335/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/2000-2010/year/2003/ | archivedate = 24 December 2018 | url-status = live | accessdate = 15 April 2020 }} Note: from 1958 to 2010 these awards were known as Australian Film Institute Awards or AFI Awards.</ref> Her two releases of 2004 - ''[[The Last Shot]]'' and ''[[Connie and Carla]]''  \u2013 were rated as having \"mixed or average reviews\" by Metacritic.<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\">{{cite web | url = https://www.metacritic.com/person/toni-collette?filter-options=movies&sort_options=metascore&num_items=100 | title = Toni Collette Movies Profile | publisher = Metacritic | access-date = 7  April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===2005\u201311: Supporting roles and ''United States of Tara''===\n\nCollette's only film in 2005, ''[[In Her Shoes (film)|In Her Shoes]]'', is a comedy-drama about the relationship between two sisters (Rose and Maggie Feller) and their estranged grandmother, co-starring [[Cameron Diaz]] and [[Shirley MacLaine]]. Based on the 2002 novel [[In Her Shoes (novel)|of the same name]] by [[Jennifer Weiner]], the film received generally positive reviews from critics, and became a moderate independent success, earning a total of US$82.2&nbsp;million worldwide.<ref>{{cite news | title = ''In Her Shoes'' (2005) | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2005/HSHOE.php | work = The Numbers |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> She was subsequently nominated for a [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Satellite Award for Best Actress]] for her performance of Rose, a successful-but-lonely lawyer with low self-esteem, which [[Mick LaSalle]] of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' noticed, \"As usual, [her] face is a fine-tuned transmitter of her emotions, moment by moment, and she becomes the locus of audience feeling.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = LaSalle | first = Mick | authorlink = Mick LaSalle | title = Oh, grow up. And move out of here while you're at it. | url = http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Oh-grow-up-And-move-out-of-here-while-you-re-at-2565906.php | accessdate = 11 December 2013 | newspaper = San Francisco Chronicle | date = 7 October 2005 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:ToniCollettOrangeBritishAcademyFilmAwards07.jpg|alt=Upper body shot of 24-year-old Collette. She has black hair and is shown in left profile and facing slightly to her right. The straps of her dress are encrusted with shiny, coloured beads.|thumbnail|Collette at the [[60th British Academy Film Awards]] in London's [[Royal Opera House]] in 2007 where she was nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for her role in ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'' (2006).|left|235x235px]]\nIn 2006 the artist starred in ''[[Little Miss Sunshine]]'', a comedy-drama [[road movie]] about a family's trip to a children's beauty pageant. It premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] in January of that year, and its distribution rights were bought by [[Fox Searchlight Pictures]] for one of the biggest deals in the history of the festival.<ref name=\"RTBiggest\">{{cite web | last = Duong | first = Senh | title = Sundance: Searchlight Spends Big for ''Little Miss Sunshine'' | url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/news/1646244/sundance-searchlight-spends-big-for-little-miss-sunshine/ | accessdate = 11 December 2013 | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | date = 21 January 2006 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121105163935/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/news/1646244/sundance-searchlight-spends-big-for-little-miss-sunshine/ | archivedate = 5 November 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> [[Sharon Waxman]] of ''The New York Times'' called her \"funny and believable\", while Stella Papamichael of [[BBC]] felt that she was \"underused.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2006/08/02/little_miss_sunshine_2006_review.shtml | title = Movies - review - ''Little Miss Sunshine'' | publisher = [[BBC]] | access-date = 8 February 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{cite news | last = Waxman | first = Sharon | authorlink = Sharon Waxman | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2006/05/07/movies/07waxm.html | title = Toni Collette, Lovely When Necessary but Vulnerable Always | date = 7 May 2006 | work = The New York Times | access-date = 4 March 2020 | issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref> The film received critical acclaim, resulting in her second BAFTA and Golden Globe nominations.<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/> It grossed US$100.5&nbsp;million worldwide and became one of the most successful independent films of the mid-2000s.<ref>{{cite web | title = ''Little Miss Sunshine'' (2006) | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2006/LMSUN.php | work = The Numbers | accessdate = 3 May 2010 }}</ref> Also in that year the actor took supporting roles in the [[thriller film]]s ''[[The Night Listener (film)|The Night Listener]]'' and ''[[The Dead Girl]]''. The latter was released to \"generally favorable\" reviews,<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/><ref>{{cite web | title = ''The Dead Girl'' (2006) | url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/dead_girl/ | work = Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate = 5 May 2010 }}</ref> while ''The Night Listener'' was higher earning with a gross revenue of US$10.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web  | title = ''The Night Listener'' (2006) | url = https://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2006/NTLIS.php | work = The Numbers | accessdate = 6 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn her first TV engagement in five years, the HBO-BBC joint miniseries ''[[Tsunami: The Aftermath]]'' (2006), she played an Australian government employee who tries to cope with the events following the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]] and the resulting [[tsunami]] in Thailand. The film received mixed reviews from critics. Robert Bianco of ''[[USA Today]]'' said that it was, \"inexcusably tasteless, tone deaf... and dull\" and Brian Lowry of ''Variety'' remarked that the film, \"[grasps] for higher ground that it never reaches.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2006/film/awards/tsunami-the-aftermath-1200511645/ | title = ''Tsunami, the Aftermath'' | last = Lowry | first = Brian | date = 6 December 2006 | work = Variety | access-date = 9 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/reviews/2006-12-07-tsunami_x.htm | title = HBO's 'Tsunami' is itself a disaster, and just wrong | work = [[USA Today]] | access-date = 9 February 2020 }}</ref> Despite this, praise was given to the performances of the cast.<ref>{{cite news | last = Heffernan | first = Virginia | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/08/arts/television/08tsun.html | title = Melodrama and, Oh Yes, a Tsunami | date = 8 December 2006 | work = The New York Times | access-date = 9 February 2020 | issn = 0362-4331 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/27874/tsunami-the-aftermath/ | title = ''Tsunami: The Aftermath'' | website = DVD Talk | access-date = 9 February 2020 }}</ref> For her role, Collette earned her first [[Primetime Emmy Award|Primetime Emmy]] nomination and third Golden Globe nomination.<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/toni-collette | title = Toni Collette | work = Television Academy | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAfter working as a juror at the [[2007 Cannes Film Festival]], she took part in two releases of 2007 - ''[[Towelhead (film)|Towelhead]]'' and ''[[Evening (film)|Evening]]''. They received \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> Kelly Vance of ''[[East Bay Express]]'', called ''Towelhead'' \"one the most intelligent films of the year\" and praised the artist's performance.<ref name=\"Vance\">{{cite news | url = https://www.eastbayexpress.com/eastbay/there-goes-the-neighborhood/Content?oid=1091720 | title = There Goes the Neighborhood | last = Vance | first = Kelly | work = [[East Bay Express]] | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref> While reviewing ''Evening'', Putman called it \"flawed in more ways than one\" but lauded her for \"[enlivening] her scenes with pathos.\"<ref name=\"Putman 2\">{{cite web| url=http://www.thefilmfile.com/reviews/e/07_evening.htm | title = Dustin's Review \u2013 ''Evening'' (2007) | last = Putman | first = Dustin | work = TheFilmFile | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref> In 2008 she played a small role in ''[[Hey, Hey, It's Esther Blueburger]]'' and also served as an [[executive producer]].<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/> Her scenes were shot in a week.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/movies/burger-with-the-lot/news-story/6022f9b9b91a33426510f5e729597d20 | title = Danielle Catanzariti Prepares to Play Big | date = 9 January 2008 | work = [[Herald Sun]] | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref> The film received tepid reviews and failed to recoup its $6 million budget. Bernadete McNulty, writing for ''The Daily Telegraph'', wrote, \"[her] presence may have got this Australian debut from writer/director Cathy Randall off the ground [but] her slight role is insufficient to make it fly the distance.\"<ref name=\"McNulty\">{{cite news | last = McNulty | first = Bernadette | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/dvd-reviews/5394834/DVD-review-Hey-Hey-Its-Esther-Blueburger.html | title = DVD review: ''Hey Hey It's Esther Blueburger'' | date = 28 July 2009 | access-date = 10 February 2020 | issn = 0307-1235 }}</ref> Her other film of 2008, ''[[The Black Balloon (film)|The Black Balloon]]'', was better received, for which she was also co-executive producer.<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/> Frank Hatherley of ''Screen Daily'' praised the film and her acting, \"[she] gives another of her warm, full-blooded portraits\" and [[Roger Ebert]] venerated her performance as being the heart of the film.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-black-balloon-2009 | title = ''The Black Balloon'' Movie Review (2009) | last = Ebert | first = Roger | authorlink = Roger Ebert | website = www.rogerebert.com | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.screendaily.com/the-black-balloon-2007/4036868.article | title = ''The Black Balloon'' (2007) | last = Hatherley | first = Frank | work = Screen Daily | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref> She won her fifth AACTA Award for the role of Maggie Mollison  in ''The Black Balloon''.<ref name=\"2008 Australian Film Institute Awards\">{{cite web | url = https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/2000-2010/year/2008/ | title = The 50th Australian Film Institute Awards (2008) Nominees and Winners | publisher = Australian Academy of Cinema and Television Arts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181224174151/https://www.aacta.org/aacta-awards/past-awards/range/2000-2010/year/2008/ | archivedate = 24 December 2018 | url-status = live | accessdate = 15 April 2020 }} Note: from 1958 to 2010 these awards were known as Australian Film Institute Awards or AFI Awards.</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Collette also accepted the leading role in the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] TV comedy-drama series, ''[[United States of Tara]]''.<ref name=\"Rothschild\"/> Created by [[Steven Spielberg]] and [[Diablo Cody]], it revolves around Tara Gregson, a wife and mother of two, who has [[dissociative identity disorder]], and is coping with alternate personalities.<ref name=\"Rothschild\"/> She was given the leading role by Spielberg without having to audition.<ref>{{cite new | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/toni-collette-5-things-you-835310/item/forces-auditions-toni-collette-835321 | title = Forces Auditions - Toni Collette: 5 Things You Didn't Know About the Actress | work = [[The Hollywood Reporter]] | access-date = 13 March 2020 }}</ref> In the role, she portrayed multiple characters and found it required her to prepare a more than she normally did.<ref name=\"Rothschild\"/> However, after she understood the characters better, she found it easier to play them.<ref name=\"Rothschild\">{{cite web | url = https://www.autostraddle.com/toni-collette-straddles-gender-roles-in-united-states-of-tara-the-autostraddle-interview-38058/ | title = Toni Collette is Queering Gender in ''United States of Tara'': The ''Autostraddle'' Interview | last = Rothschild | first = Jess | date = 22 March 2010 | work = [[Autostraddle]] | access-date = 10 April 2020 }}</ref> The show was originally planned for a twelve-episode season, but was renewed for a second and third season after it gave the network its highest ratings since 2004.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.multichannel.com/article/173970-Showtime_United_With_Tara_For_Second_Season.php | title = Showtime United with Tara for Second Season | last = Umstead | first = Thomas R. | work = [[Multichannel News]] | date = 10 February 2009 | access-date = 10 February 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090214045815/http://www.multichannel.com/article/173970-Showtime_United_With_Tara_For_Second_Season.php | archive-date  =14 February 2009 }}</ref> The series and her performance received \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref name=\"Metacritic TV list\"/> Tim Goodman of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' called her a \"tour de force\" and Ariana Bacle of ''Entertainment Weekly'' praised the actor's \"flawless\" transition between personalities that felt so \"insanely distinct\" that they could have each been a different actor.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://ew.com/article/2014/02/10/im-still-not-over-united-states-of-tara-cancellation/ | title = I'm Still Not Over... ''United States of Tara'' getting canceled | work = Entertainment Weekly | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url  =https://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/TV-review-United-States-of-Tara-3254262.php | title = TV review: ''United States of Tara'' | last = Goodman | first = Tim | date = 16 January 2009 | work = San Francisco Chronicle | access-date = 10 February 2020 }}</ref> Collette won both the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe for Best Actress in a TV Comedy]] in 2009 and was nominated for both again in the following year.<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/> Also in 2009 she lent her voice to the critically acclaimed [[Stop motion|stop-motion]] [[Comedy-drama|dramedy]] ''[[Mary and Max]].''\n\nShe was originally set to star in ''[[Away We Go]]'' (2009) but dropped out due to scheduling conflicts. The artist next starred as a single mother of a precocious child in ''[[Jesus Henry Christ]]'' (2011).<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> The film received \"mixed or average reviews\";<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> James Plath of ''Movie Metropolis'' called her \"terrific\" but John DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' felt that she was severely underutilised.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://moviemet.com/review/jesus-henry-christ-dvd-review | title = ''Jesus Henry Christ'' - DVD Review | date = 3 July 2012 | website = Movie Metropolis | access-date = 11 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/jesus-henry-christ-film-review-183323 | title = ''Jesus Henry Christ'': Tribeca Review | work = The Hollywood Reporter | access-date = 11 February 2020 }}</ref> She later had a supporting role in the horror-comedy [[Fright Night (2011 film)|''Fright Night'']] (2011). The film reunited her with film-maker [[Craig Gillespie]] who had directed her in several episodes of ''United States of Tara''.<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2011/film/reviews/fright-night-1117945839/ | title = ''Fright Night'' | last = Koehler | first = Robert | date = 18 August 2011 | work = Variety | access-date = 11 February 2020 }}</ref> Debbie Lynn Elias of ''Behind the Lens'' called her \"pitchfork perfect\" while Emmet Asher-Perrin of ''[[Tor.com]]'' said that she was \"charming as always.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.tor.com/2011/08/23/one-of-lifes-guilty-pleasures-fright-night/ | title = One of Life's Guilty Pleasures: ''Fright Night'' | last = Asher-Perrin | first = Emmet | date = 23 August 2011 | website = [[Tor.com]] | access-date = 11 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://behindthelensonline.net/site/reviews/fright-night/ | title = ''Fright Night'' | last = Elias | first = Debbie Lynn | website = Behind the Lens | access-date = 11 February 2020 }}</ref> The film received \"generally favorable reviews,\"<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> and was a commercial success grossing US$41&nbsp;million on a US$30&nbsp;million budget.\n\n===2012\u201317: Independent films and Broadway return===\n\nCollette's first release of 2012 was the independent comedy-drama ''[[Mental (2012 film)|Mental]]''. She played Shaz, a hitchhiker who is hired as a [[nanny]] to take care of five [[mentally ill]] sisters. Despite giving the film a negative review, Gary Goldstein of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said that the actor \"rips into her woolly role as if channeling a leftover personality from her ''United States of Tara'' days.\"<ref>{{Cite news | url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-xpm-2013-mar-28-la-et-mn-mental-capsule-review-20130329-story.html | title = Review: In a Fragile ''Mental'' State | date = 28 March 2013 | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | access-date = 16 February 2020 }}</ref> Luke Buckmaster of ''[[Crikey]]'' called her \"charismatic and all-inhabiting.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://blogs.crikey.com.au/cinetology/2012/10/08/mental-movie-review-crazy-good-aussie-filmmaking/ | title = ''Mental'' Movie Review: Crazy Good Aussie Filmmaking \u2013 Cinetology | website = [[Crikey]] | access-date = 16 February 2020 }}</ref> She received her third AACTA Award for Best Actress nomination for the role. Later in the year, she played [[Peggy Robertson|Peggy]], a supporting role in the [[Biographical film|biographical]] drama, ''[[Hitchcock (film)|Hitchcock]]''. [[Deborah Ross (journalist)|Deborah Ross]], writing for ''[[The Spectator]]'', provided an unenthusiastic review and wrote, \"[it] wastes many of its cast members - particularly Toni Collette.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.spectator.co.uk/2013/02/whats-it-all-about-3/ | title = What kind of film does ''Hitchcock'' think it is? | last = Ross | first = Deborah | authorlink = Deborah Ross (journalist) | date = 9 February 2013 | work = [[The Spectator]] | access-date = 16 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Toni Collette (8968233309).jpg|alt=|thumb|275x275px|alt=The 40-year-old is shown in upper body shot. She is facing slightly to her left and wears a biege dress with black triangles. Her fair to light brown hairs falls to her shoulders. Behind her is a largely light blue backdrop.|Collette at ''[[The Way Way Back]]'' premiere at the State Theatre, Sydney in 2013]]\nIn 2013 the artist earned critical acclaim for her work in the independent film ''[[The Way, Way Back]]'' as Pam, opposite [[Steve Carell]] and [[Sam Rockwell]], and in ''[[Enough Said (film)|Enough Said]]'' as Sarah, with [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]] and [[James Gandolfini]]. For ''The Way, Way Back'', she received positive reviews: Andrew O'Hehir of ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' praised her \"brilliant, understated performance;\"<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.salon.com/2013/07/05/pick_of_the_week_the_way_way_back_is_a_wistful_summer_escape/ | url-access = subscription | title = Pick of the Week: ''The Way, Way Back'' Is a Wistful Summer Escape | first = Andrew | last = O'Hehir | date = 5 July 2013 | work = [[Salon (website)|Salon]] | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' dubbed her work \"stellar;\"<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-way-way-back-20130708 | first = Peter | last = Travers | title = ''The Way Way Back'' | date = 8 July 2013 | work = [[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> Berardinelli described her as a \"chameleon\" and said that she gives a performance far and above what the role required.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.reelviews.net/php_review_template.php?identifier=2639 | title = Reviews: ''The Way Way Back'' | first = James | last = Berardinelli | date = 16 July 2013 | work = Reelviews Movie Reviews | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> Her performance in ''Enough Said'' was also well received; Katie Smith-Wong of ''FlickFeast'' praised her for bringing humour to the film but Joseph Walsh of ''CinVue'' said that she was underused.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.flickfeast.co.uk/reviews/film-reviews/enoughsaid-2013-2/ | title = ''Enough Said'' (2013) | date = 17 October 2013 | work = FlickFeast | access-date = 18 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = https://cine-vue.com/2013/10/lff-2013-enough-said-review.html | title = LFF 2013: ''Enough Said'' Review | date = 20 October 2013 | website = CineVue | access-date = 18 February 2020 }}</ref> Later that year, Collette starred in the CBS TV drama, ''[[Hostages (American TV series)|Hostages]]'', which received \"general favorable reviews,\"<ref name=\"Metacritic TV list\"/> but weak ratings. ''[[RedEye]]''{{'}}s Curt Wagner described her performance as \"fascinating,\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.redeyechicago.com/entertainment/tv/redeye-blacklist-hostages-tv-reviews-20130922,0,3522892.story | title = Monday suspense TV: 'The Blacklist' has edge over 'Hostages' | first = Curt | last = Wagner | date = 22 September 2013 | work = [[RedEye]] | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> Verne Gay of ''[[Newsday]]'' as \"superb,\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/hostages-review-thrill-ride-1.6109696 | title = ''Hostages'' Review: Thrill Ride | first = Verne | last = Gay | date = 20 September 2013 | work = [[Newsday]] | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> and ''USA Today''{{'}}s Bianco as \"nuanced\" and \"grounded.\"<ref>{{cite news | url  =https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2013/09/22/bianco-blacklist-hostages-combo-review-sept-23/2831619/ | work = USA Today | first1 = Robert | last1 = Bianco | title = ''Blacklist'', ''Hostages'' Each Have Suspenseful Charms | date = 22 September 2013 }}</ref> The series aired for fifteen episodes and, due to a combination of low ratings and a closed narrative, did not return for a second season.\n\nIn the comedy-drama ''[[Lucky Them]]'' (2013), which debuted at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]], Collette portrayed Ellie Klug, a music critic assigned to write about a disappeared musician and childhood sweetheart, and tasked herself to track him down. She took on the role because she felt the script had a realistic and in-depth approach to topics like [[Self-sustainability|self-sufficiency]] and [[self-realization]].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2014/03/28/toni-collette-on-a-new-play-and-why-she-shaved-her-head/|title=Toni Collette On \u2018The Realistic Joneses\u2019 and Why She Shaved Her Head|last=Cohen|first=Stefanie|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> She later said that, out of all the roles she had played, Ellie resembled her the most.<ref name=\":9\" /> The film earned \"generally favorable reviews,\" with her receiving praise.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.villagevoice.com/2014-05-28/film/lucky-them-movie/ | title = The Nimble ''Lucky Them'' Seeks Out a Grunge Legend | first = Chris | last = Packham | date = 28 May 2014 | work = [[The Village Voice]] | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://nypost.com/2014/05/28/indie-charmer-lucky-them-boasts-a-rock-solid-cast/ | work = New York Post | first = Lou | last = Lumenick | title = Indie Charmer ''Lucky Them'' Boasts a Rock Solid Cast | date = 28 May 2014 }}</ref> David Rooney of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' wrote that it was \"centered by smart, soulful work by the wonderful Toni Collette\" and that she played her character \"with warmth, realness and emotional transparency that make you stay with her even when she's pushing people away.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/lucky-toronto-review-625953 | work = The Hollywood Reporter | first = David | last = Rooney | title = ''Lucky Them'': Toronto Review | date = 11 September 2013 }}</ref> The film also screened at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]], where Joe Bendel of ''[[Libertas Film Magazine]]'' ranked her performance as the fourth-best of the festival.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.indiewire.com/article/results-of-the-2014-tribeca-critics-poll | title = Critics Pick the Best Movies at the Tribeca Film Festival | first = Steve | last = Greene | date = 29 April 2014 | work = [[IndieWire]] | accessdate = 18 September 2015}}</ref> Upon its release, [[Mike D'Angelo]] of ''[[The Dissolve]]'' wrote that she \"is capable of anything.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://thedissolve.com/reviews/832-lucky-them/ | accessdate = 8 July 2015 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150324181848/https://thedissolve.com/reviews/832-lucky-them/ | archivedate = 24 March 2015 | title = ''Lucky Them'' | last = Klimek | first = Chris | date = 29 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAfter a 14-year absence, Collette returned to Broadway in 2014, starring as Jennifer Jones in [[Will Eno]]'s play ''[[The Realistic Joneses]]'', in which she co-starred alongside Marisa Tomei, [[Michael C. Hall]], and [[Tracy Letts]]. The play examines a couple who project their insecurities and fears onto their next-door neighbors with the same last name. The play opened to positive reviews, with the actor, and the entire cast, earning high praise.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Review-Roundup-THE-REALISTIC-JONESES-Opens-on-Broadway-Updating-Live-20140406# | title = Review Roundup: ''The Realistic Joneses'' Opens on Broadway | work = [[BroadwayWorld]] | date = 6 April 2014 | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> Charles Isherwood from ''The New York Times'' wrote that \"Ms. Collette exudes a touching, exasperated dignity as Jennifer.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/07/theater/realistic-joneses-stars-toni-collette-and-michael-c-hall.html | title = ''Realistic Joneses'' Stars Toni Collette and Michael C. Hall | last = Isherwood | first = Charles | newspaper = The New York Times | date = 7 April 2014 | url-access = subscription }}</ref> ''Variety''{{'}}s Marilyn Stasio called her work \"terribly funny,\"<ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-the-realistic-joneses-1201153252/ | title = Broadway Review: ''The Realistic Joneses'' | first = Marilyn | last = Stasio | work = Variety | date = 6 April 2014 | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> while Rooney of ''The Hollywood Reporter'' claimed that her \"naturalness can cut through even the very deliberate theatrical artifice of Eno's dialogue and scene construction, anchors the play with her somber restraint and deadpan delivery.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/theater-review-realistic-joneses-693966 | title = Theater Review: ''The Realistic Joneses'' | first = David | last = Rooney | work = Hollywood Reporter | date = 6 April 2014 | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> The ''[[New York Post]]''{{'}}s Elisabeth Vincentelli, who was more critical of the play, highlighted her performance: \"[she] does some heavy lifting to fill in Eno's blanks. You can read deep sadness in the wide planes of her expressive face, in her lost, unfocused eyes.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://nypost.com/2014/04/06/eno-packs-powerhouse-quartet-in-the-realistic-joneses/ | title = Eno packs powerhouse quartet in ''The Realistic Joneses'' | first = Elisabeth | last = Vincentelli | newspaper = New York Post | date = 6 April 2014 | accessdate = 18 September 2015 }}</ref> The artist and her co-stars won a [[Drama Desk Special Award]] for Best Ensemble Performance.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://variety.com/2014/legit/news/gentlemans-guide-racks-up-a-dozen-nominations-for-the-2014-drama-desk-awards-1201163848/ | work = Variety | first = Gordon | last = Cox | title = ''Gentleman's Guide'' Racks Up 12 Nominations for Drama Desk Awards | date = 25 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Collette appeared in three comedy films, ''[[Tammy (film)|Tammy]]'', ''[[A Long Way Down (film)|A Long Way Down]]'' and ''[[Hector and the Search for Happiness (film)|Hector and the Search for Happiness]]''.<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> All are rated as having \"generally unfavorable reviews\" by Metacritic.<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> Also that year she provided the voice to Lady Portley-Rind in the animated film, ''[[The Boxtrolls]]''.<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> She starred as Milly opposite [[Drew Barrymore]] as Jess in the comedy-drama ''[[Miss You Already]]'' (2015), about two women whose friendship is tested when Jess starts a family while Milly falls ill. It premiered at the Toronto International Film Festival to generally positive reviews; more widely, Metacritic rated it at 59% indicating, \"mixed or average reviews.\" Billy Goodykoontz of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' asserted that \"[her] work is so compulsively watchable that ''Miss You Already'' is worth a watch for that reason alone.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.azcentral.com/story/entertainment/movies/billgoodykoontz/2015/11/05/miss-you-already-old-fashioned-weepie-movie-review/75134050/ | title = Review: ''Miss You Already'' an Old-fashioned Weepie | first = Billy | last = Goodykoontz | work = [[The Arizona Republic]] | date = 5 November 2015 | accessdate = 11 February 2020 }}</ref> Collette then played the matriarch of a dysfunctional family in the horror film ''[[Krampus (film)|Krampus]]'' (also 2015), which was a commercial success, grossing $61.5 million against a budget of $15 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web | url = https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=krampus.htm | title = ''Krampus'' (2015)| website = [[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate = 10 March 2016 }}</ref> Her sole release of 2016 was the crime thriller ''[[Imperium]]'', opposite [[Daniel Radcliffe]], she portrayed Angela Zamparo, an FBI analyst targeting a white supremacist group. Despite its limited release, the film garnered positive reviews, with Gary Goldstein of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' calling it \"impressively dimensional...tense, gripping and disturbing,\" and found her to be \"excellent\" as Radcliffe's character's supervisor.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-imperium-review-20160816-snap-story.html | url-access = subscription | title = Daniel Radcliffe Goes Undercover with White Supremacists in Crime Thriller ''Imperium'' | first = Gary | last = Goldstein | work = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = 17 August 2016 | accessdate = 21 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Collette appeared in several films: to varying degrees of success. The action film, ''[[XXX: Return of Xander Cage]]'', starring [[Vin Diesel]], was a commercial success, grossing $346.1 million<ref name=\"BOM2\">{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=xxx3.htm | title = ''xXx: The Return of Xander Cage'' (2017) | work = Box Office Mojo | accessdate = 22 April 2017 }}</ref> and earned mixed reviews, though Mick LaSalle of the ''San Francisco Chronicle'' praised her for \"embrac[ing] the cold-blooded extremes of her role\" as a CIA operative.<ref name=\"LaSalle\">{{cite web | url = https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/XXX-Return-of-Xander-Cage-OK-if-10869299.php | title = ''XXX: Return of Xander Cage'' \u2014 OK if You're in on the joke | last = LaSalle | first = Mick | work = San Francisco Chronicle | date = 19 January 2017 | access-date = 12 April 2020 }}</ref> Her next two films \u2014 the war drama ''[[The Yellow Birds (film)|The Yellow Birds]]'' and the comedy ''[[Fun Mom Dinner]]'' \u2014 premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sundance.org/pdf/film-guide/SFF17_FilmGuide_Web_Dec12.pdf | title = 2017 Sundance Film Festival: Printable Film Guide | publisher = [[The Sundance Institute]] | accessdate = 13 December 2016 }}</ref> Both gathered \"mixed or average reviews,\"<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> though the actor's work was appreciated, particularly in the former, with Michael Rechtshaffen of the ''Los Angeles Times'' taking note of how she, and co-star [[Jennifer Aniston]], \"deliver uniformly naturalistic performances.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-yellow-birds-review-20180614-story.html | title = Though Well-Acted, ''The Yellow Birds'' Relies too Heavily on Previous War Dramas | first = Michael | last = Rechtshaffen | work = Los Angeles Times | date = 14 June 2018 | accessdate = 12 February 2020 }}</ref> She was also in the action-thriller ''[[Unlocked (2017 film)|Unlocked]]'', and the comedies ''[[Madame (2017 film)|Madame]]'' and ''[[Please Stand By]]'', all of which received \"mixed or average reviews\" according to Metacritic.<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> The mystery drama ''[[Jasper Jones (film)|Jasper Jones]]'' (2017) was better received \u2013 obtaining 77% at Rotten Tomatoes.<ref name=\"Rotten Jasper\">{{cite web | url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jasper_jones | title = ''Jasper Jones'' (2016) | publisher = Rotten Tomatoes | date = | access-date = 12 April 2020 }}</ref> Sandra Hall of ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]'' praised her emotional range and James Douglas, writing for ''The Guardian'', said that she was \"impossibly vivacious as always.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Douglas | first = James Robert | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/aug/25/jasper-jones-first-look-review-spielberg-meets-stranger-things-in-australian-coming-of-age-tale | title = ''Jasper Jones'' First Look Review \u2013 Spielberg meets ''Stranger Things' in Australian Coming-of-Age Tale | date = 25 August 2016 | work = The Guardian | access-date = 27 February 2020 | issn = 0261-3077 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/jasper-jones-review-a-classic-tale-well-told-20170227-gum3uf.html | title = ''Jasper Jones'' Review: A Classic Tale Well Told | last = Hall | first = Sandra | date = 28 February 2017 | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 27 February 2020 }}</ref> Richard Kuipers of ''Variety'' eulogized the artist's climactic monologue in which her character laments her discontent, calling her \"positively electrifying.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/jasper-jones-film-review-1201999791/ | title = Film Review: ''Jasper Jones'' | last = Kuipers | first = Richard | date = 2 March 2017 | work = Variety | accessdate = 27 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in that year she formed a production company, Vocab Films, with her US-based talent manager Jen Turner.<ref name=\"Busch\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2017/05/toni-collette-graeme-simsion-the-best-of-adam-sharp-vocab-films-1202099473/ | title = Toni Collette Options Graeme Simsion Novel ''The Best of Adam Sharp'' for Her Vocab Films | last = Busch | first = Anita | work = [[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] | date = 23 May 2017 | access-date = 13 April 2020 }}</ref> She had previously worked as executive producer for the films she appeared in, ''Like Minds'' (2006), ''The Black Balloon'', and ''Hey, Hey, It's Esther Blueburger'' (both 2008).<ref name=\"BFI Filmography\"/> Vocab Film's first project is ''[[The Best of Adam Sharp]]'' (2016), a novel by fellow Australian, [[Graeme Simsion]].<ref name=\"Busch\"/> Collette is set to play the female lead role, Angelina Brown, who is described by Anita Busch of ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' as, \"an intelligent and strong-willed woman... who taught [Adam] what it meant to find\u2014and then lose\u2014love.\"<ref name=\"Busch\"/> Another project is Julia Dahl's novel, ''Invisible City'', which is a co-production with [[RadicalMedia]], for a TV murder mystery with the actor also working as a script writer for the pilot episode.<ref name=\"Berger\">{{cite web | url = https://womenandhollywood.com/toni-collette-to-ep-and-write-tv-adaptation-of-julia-dahls-invisible-city-92b3c8361306/?source=rss----eb0b08436136---4 | title = Toni Collette to EP and Write TV Adaptation of Julia Dahl's ''Invisible City'' | last = Berger | first = Laura | work = Women and Hollywood | date = 13 July 2017 | access-date = 13 April 2020 }}</ref> She explained her motivation, \"it's about fighting for personal freedom and living an authentic life. It couldn't be a more relevant time to tell this story about acceptance and integration, or lack thereof. These complex female characters are honest, flawed, and inspiring. We can always use more of those.\"<ref name=\"Berger\"/>\n\n===2018\u2013present: Mainstream films and Netflix===\n\nIn 2018 Collette gave what some critics considered to be one of her best performances of in the horror film ''[[Hereditary (film)|Hereditary]]'', in which she played Annie Graham, the matriarch of a family haunted by the supernatural following the death of her mother.<ref name=rolling>{{cite journal | url = https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-features/hereditary-inside-the-making-of-a-modern-horror-classic-629141/ | title = ''Hereditary'': Inside the Making of a Modern Horror Classic | author = Fear, David | work = Rolling Stone | date = 12 June 2018 | accessdate = 23 December 2018 }}</ref> She was initially reluctant to take on the role, but became convinced by the script's grounded approach and its exploration of grief and loss.<ref name=\":2\" /> She considered it to be the most difficult of her career: in an interview with ''[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]''{{'}}s Rachel Handler she reflected, \"There was no easy moment in this movie... I was shooting 14-take scenes, talking about great loss and difficulty in relating to my family.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vulture.com/2018/06/toni-collette-on-hereditary-the-wildest-movie-of-her-career.html | title = Toni Collette on ''Hereditary'', the Wildest Movie of Her Career | last = Handler | first = Rachel | date = 8 June 2018 | website = [[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] | accessdate = 15 February 2020 }}</ref> The film premiered at the Sundance Film Festival to critical acclaim, and it became [[A24 (company)|A24]]'s highest-grossing film, earning US$80.2&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web |url = https://www.sundance.org/projects/hereditary | title = ''Hereditary'' | publisher = The Sundance Institute | accessdate = 31 July 2018 }}</ref> Chris Nashawaty of ''Entertainment Weekly'' praised her for \"real dramatic power and force,\" while Michael Phillips of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' complimented her \"fierce performance with a human pulse.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-hereditary-rev-0604-story.html | title = ''Hereditary'' Review: Toni Collette Reveals a Sixth Sense for Icy Terror | last = Phillips | first  = Michael | work = [[Chicago Tribune]] | accessdate = 21 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = https://ew.com/movies/2018/06/08/hereditary-movie-review-toni-collette/ | title = Toni Collette Is Scary Good in the Terrifying ''Hereditary'': EW Review | work = Entertainment Weekly | accessdate = 21 June 2018 }}</ref> She won the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Best Actress]] and was nominated for the [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]] for her performance.<ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"Wagmeister\">{{cite journal | last1 = Wagmeister | first1 = Elizabeth | title = Gotham Awards: A24 Sweeps with Five Wins, Including ''First Reformed'', ''Eighth Grade'' (Full Winners List) | url = https://variety.com/2018/film/news/gotham-awards-winners-list-2018-new-york-1203037073/ | accessdate = 12 April 2020 | work = Variety | date = 26 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\n''[[Wanderlust (British TV series)|Wanderlust]]'' (2018), a [[BBC One]] TV drama series about the troubled relationship between Collette's character, Joy Richards, a therapist, and her husband.<ref name=\"Szalai\">{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/toni-collette-leads-cast-bbc-netflixs-wanderlust-1055852 | title = Toni Collette Leads Cast of BBC, Netflix's ''Wanderlust'' | last = Szalai | first = Georg | work = Hollywood Reporter | date = 7 November 2017 | accessdate = 19 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Metacritic TV list\"/> It was her first lead role in TV series since ''Hostages''. She also served as an associate producer on the series.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web | url = https://www.indiewire.com/2018/10/wanderlust-netflix-review-toni-collette-bbc-1202013432/ | title = ''Wanderlust'' Review: Toni Collette's Dominance of 2018 Continues in a Smart Netflix Series That's Honest About Sex | last = Travers | first = Ben | date = 19 October 2018 | work = IndieWire | accessdate = 4 March 2020 }}</ref> Ben Travers of ''[[IndieWire]]'' wrote \"[she guides] the [series] through turbulent emotional seas with assurance\" and Jen Chaney of ''Vulture'' remarked that the show was worth watching solely for her performance.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/wanderlust-netflix-review.html | title = In ''Wanderlust'', Toni Collette Gets Serious About Sex | last = Chaney | first = Jen | date = 19 October 2018 | website = Vulture | accessdate = 4 March 2020 }}</ref> Also that year, she appeared in the critically acclaimed comedy ''[[Hearts Beat Loud]]'',<ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/> which also premiered at Sundance. [[Peter Bradshaw]] called it \"a likable heartwarmer\" and praised the actor for \"[giving the] film some sinew in her supporting role.\"<ref name=\"Bradshaw\">{{cite web | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/aug/03/hearts-beat-loud-review-warm-indie-drama | title = ''Hearts Beat Loud'' Review \u2013 Warm Indie Drama Film | last = Bradshaw | first = Peter | work = The Guardian | date = 3 August 2018 | access-date = 12 April 2020 }}</ref> In the following year the actor returned to the horror genre in [[Dan Gilroy]]'s ''[[Velvet Buzzsaw]]'', alongside [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] and [[Rene Russo]]. Partly a satire about the art world, it premiered at the Sundance Film Festival to polarising reactions. ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''{{'}} [[Richard Roeper]] gave it a positive review, \"[she is] as good as we\u2019d expect [her] to be.\"<ref name=\"Roeper\">{{cite web | url = https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/2/1/18375659/velvet-buzzsaw-netflix-movie-funny-as-an-art-attack | title = ''Velvet Buzzsaw'': Netflix movie funny as an art attack - Chicago Sun-Times | last = Roeper | first = Richard | work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]] | date = 1 February 2019 | accessdate = 12 April 2020 }}</ref> She played a supporting role as Joni Thrombey in [[Rian Johnson]]'s critically acclaimed mystery thriller ''[[Knives Out]]'', alongside an ensemble cast including [[Daniel Craig]], [[Ana de Armas]], [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], and [[Christopher Plummer]]. It premiered at the Toronto International Film Festival and was a commercial success, grossing US$300.1 million. Critics highlighted the performances of the cast: [[Joe Morgenstern]] wrote that Collette \"nails her character\u2019s style with elan\" and David Rooney considered her to be \"divine as a deeply sincere phony.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/knives-out-tiff-2019-1237825 | title = ''Knives Out'': Film Review {{!}} TIFF 2019 | last = Rooney | first = David | date = 7 September 2019 | work = The Hollywood Reporter | url-status = live | accessdate = 12 September 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190909090941/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/knives-out-tiff-2019-1237825 | archive-date = 9 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/knives-out-review-the-giddy-pleasures-of-virtuosity-11574884919|title=\u2018Knives Out\u2019 Review: The Giddy Pleasures of Virtuosity|last=Morgenstern|first=Joe|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nCollette took the role of a detective, Grace Rasmussen, investigating a troubling rape case, with [[Merritt Wever]] and [[Kaitlyn Dever]], in the [[Netflix]] miniseries, ''[[Unbelievable (miniseries)|Unbelievable]]'' (2019). She had accepted it prior to reading the script, finding the topic, \"important and so meaningful.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://collider.com/toni-collette-interview-unbelievable/#nightmare-alley-knives-out | title = Toni Collette on ''Unbelievable'', ''Knives Out'' and ''Nightmare Alley'' | last = Radish | first = Christina | date = 13 September 2019 | website = [[Collider (website)|Collider]] | url-status = live | accessdate = 12 April 2020 }}</ref> She prepared for the role by having a female cop on set who helped her with such particulars as where to place badges and guns and how to stage a medical examination with a rape victim.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://nypost.com/2019/09/10/script-for-unbelievable-made-toni-collettes-blood-boil/ | title = Script for ''Unbelievable'' Made Toni Collette's Blood Boil | last = Rorke | first = Robert | date = 10 September 2019 | work = New York Post | accessdate = 17 March 2020 }}</ref> It had been seen by over 32&nbsp;million people making it one of Netflix's highest viewed TV series.<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite news | url = https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/netflix-has-revealed-its-most-watched-content-you-might-be-surprised-1.4060255 | title = Netflix Has Revealed Its Most-Watched Content. You Might Be Surprised | last = Lee | first = Benjamin | date = 23 October 2019 | work = [[The Irish Times]] | url-status = live | accessdate = 13 April 2020 }}</ref> The artist received acclaim for her performance and several critics praised her chemistry with Wever:<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hale|first=Mike|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/13/arts/television/review-netflix-unbelievable.html|title=Netflix\u2019s \u2018Unbelievable\u2019 Retells a Confounding Story of Injustice|date=2019-09-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Jen Chaney of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' wrote, \"Wever and Collette both create fully authentic women who ooze integrity but also have enough insecurities and make enough mistakes to seem like actual human beings\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/unbelievable-netflix-review.html|title=Unbelievable Is a Radical, Exceptional Crime Series|last=Chaney|first=Jen|date=2019-09-13|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  She received her sixth [[Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Award]] nomination and won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Movie/Miniseries]]. In 2020 she took on a leading role in [[Dream Horse (film)|''Dream Horse'']] playing a middle-aged [[South Wales]] native who decides to train a racehorse. Dennis Harvey of ''Variety'' praised her for \"easily [carrying] the film\u2019s emotional weight.\" She is due to appear in two Netflix projects; the thriller series, ''[[Pieces of Her (TV series)|Pieces of Her]]'' and [[Charlie Kaufman]]'s ''[[I'm Thinking of Ending Things (film)|I'm Thinking of Ending Things]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url  =https://deadline.com/2020/02/pieces-of-her-toni-collette-star-netflix-thriller-series-minkie-spiro-direct-1202848386/ | title = Toni Collette to Star in ''Pieces of Her'' Netflix Drama Series | last1 = Andreeva | first1 = Nellie  |last2 = Petski | first2 = Denise | date = 3 February 2020 | work = Deadline Hollywood | accessdate = 3 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toni-collette-jessie-buckley-and-david-thewlis-join-charlie-kaufmans-netflix-movie-exclusive-1203172412/ | title = Toni Collette, Jessie Buckley and David Thewlis Join Charlie Kaufman's Netflix Movie (Exclusive) | last = Kroll | first = Justin | date = 26 March 2019 | work = Variety | accessdate = 4 March 2020 }}</ref> She has also committed to appear in the science fiction thriller, ''[[Stowaway (upcoming film)|Stowaway]]'' and [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s ''[[Nightmare Alley (upcoming film)|Nightmare Alley]]'' (all 2020).<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toni-collette-anna-kendrick-stowaway-1203107585/ | title = Toni Collette Joins Anna Kendrick in Sci-Fi Thriller ''Stowaway'' (Exclusive) | last = Kroll | first = Justin | date = 15 January 2019 | journal = Variety | accessdate = 4 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Music career==\n\n[[File:Miss You Already 05 (20764762454) (2) (cropped).jpg|thumb|240x240px|alt=The 42-year-old is shown in a half-body shot. She wears a white top above a yellow skirt. She is smiling and facing to her left with her hair short, fair to light brown. Behing her to our left is a man wearing headphones and a microphone, while at the right is a woman holding an umbrella.|Collette at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] premiere of ''[[Miss You Already]]'' (2015)]]\nDespite cherishing music and singing at a young age, Collette had stopped in the mid-1990s and explained, \"[Singing] comes from a very personal place. It's your voice... and it's only in the last couple of years I felt comfortable in myself singing.\" In 1996 she sang three cover versions for the soundtrack of the film, ''Cosi'': \"[[Don't Dream It's Over]]\" (originally by Crowded House), \"[[Stand by Me (Ben E. King song)|Stand By Me]]\" (Ben E. King) and \"[[Throw Your Arms Around Me]]\" (Hunters & Collectors).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://ringostrack.com:443/en/movie/cosi/81853 | title = ''Cosi'' (1996) Soundtrack | website = RingosTrack | accessdate = 13 February 2020 }}</ref> In 2000 she recorded nine tracks for the cast album, ''The Wild Party'', for the eponymous Broadway musical.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.amazon.com/Wild-Party-Various-artists/dp/B000V889OK | title = ''The Wild Party'' | website = [[Amazon.com]] | accessdate = 13 March 2020 }}</ref> Elyse Sommer of ''CurtainUp,'' in a review of the musical, wrote that she was a \"topnotch singer\" and particularly praised her rendition of \"People Like Us\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.curtainup.com/wildparty2.html | title = ''The Wild Party'', a ''CurtainUp'' review | website = CurtainUp | accessdate = 13 March 2020 }}</ref> For the soundtrack of ''Connie and Carla'' (2004), Collette, and her co-star [[Nia Vardalos]], recorded duets of several show tunes including, \"[[I'm Gonna Wash That Man Right Outa My Hair]]\", \"[[Maybe This Time (song)|Maybe This Time]]\" and \"[[Cabaret (Cabaret song)|Cabaret]]\".<ref name=\"ConnieCarla\"/><ref name=\"Stein\"/> David Haviland of ''Eye for Film'' praised the renditions, \"The musical numbers are a [[Camp (style)|camp]] triumph.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/review/connie-and-carla-do-la-film-review-by-david-haviland | title = ''Connie and Carla'' Do LA (2004) Movie Review from ''Eye for Film'' | website = Eye for Film | accessdate = 13 March 2020 }}</ref> She sang the track, \"Sunday Morning\", for the album ''[[Summertown (album)|Summertown]]'' by [[Deborah Conway]] and Willy Zygier. She has also performed songs for soundtracks of ''About a Boy'', ''A Long Way Down'', ''Miss You Already'' and ''Hearts Beat Loud''.\n\nCollette has been writing her own songs since early teens.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite news | last = Dubecki | first = Larissa | url = https://www.smh.com.au/news/music/tonis-hidden-talent/2006/11/01/1162339920182.html?page=fullpage | title = Toni's Hidden Talent | date = 3 November 2006 | newspaper = The Sydney Morning Herald | accessdate = 11 December 2013 }}</ref> In 2006 with encouragement of her husband Dave Galafassi on drums (ex-[[Gelbison]]), she formed [[Toni Collette & the Finish]] in Sydney.<ref name=\":8\"/><ref name=\"Collar\">{{cite web | url = https://www.allmusic.com/artist/toni-collette-mn0002060163/biography | title = Toni Collette &#124; Biography & History | last = Collar | first = Matt | publisher = [[AllMusic]] | accessdate = 13 April 2020 }} Note: to access further information select a tab, e.g. Songs. </ref> Also joining the band were [[Amanda Brown (musician)|Amanda Brown]] on keyboards, [[Glenn Richards]] on guitar, [[David Lane (musician)|David Lane]] on piano and keyboards and Pete Farley on bass guitar.<ref name=\":8\"/><ref name=\"Moran\"/> Their first gig was at The Basement, Sydney, \"I was completely petrified and I think once I got that out of the way, I have just been enjoying it... In the acting, the film world, they try to hide things from actors, keep them cushioned. So I am really enjoying getting my hands dirty.\"<ref name=\"Moran\">{{cite news | url = https://www.news.com.au/national/toni-collette-getting-used-to-live-gigs/news-story/738f61776b7a64e3a8dc5678decccc23 | title = Toni Collette 'Getting Used to Live Gigs' | last = Moran | first = Jonothan | work = www.news.com | date = 17 March 2009 | access-date = 15 April 2020 | agency =[[Australian Associated Press]] (AAP) }}</ref> On 9 October 2006 the band issued their debut album, ''Beautiful Awkward Pictures'', on Hoola Hoop Records. Using her personal life as an inspiration, she wrote all eleven&nbsp;tracks under her married name, '''Toni Collette-Galafassi'''.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite news | title = The Little Drummer Girl | last = Mordue | first = Mark | date = 30 November 2006 | work = The Sydney Morning Herald }}</ref><ref name=\"APRA Beautiful\">{{cite web | url = http://apraamcos.com.au/search?searchtype=works&keywords=beautiful+awkward+pictures | title = Works Search: Title 'Beautiful Awkward Pictures' | publisher = [[APRA AMCOS]] | accessdate = 4 April 2020 }}</ref> It was recorded in two weeks: Collette co-produced with [[Deborah Conway#Conway and Zygier|Zygier]].<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\"NLA TC&tF\">{{citation | author1 = Collette, Toni | author2 = Finish | title = Beautiful Awkward Pictures | publication-date = 2006 | publisher = Hoola Hoop Records | url = https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/34266154 | accessdate = 14 April 2020 | quote = Recorded at The Shed on 10-24 January 2006 }}</ref> Eclectic of ''[[Sputnikmusic]]'' gave it a positive review, \"Collette's subdued vocals aren't perfect, but they're close enough to love all the same.\" He did, however, rebuke the lyrics of some tracks remarking that they had \"some stunningly bad lines.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/41593/Toni-Collette-and-The-Finish-Beautiful-Awkward-Pictures/|title=Toni Collette and The Finish - ''Beautiful Awkward Pictures'' (album review ) {{!}} Sputnikmusic|website=www.sputnikmusic.com|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> The album provided two singles, \"Beautiful Awkward Pictures\" (September 2006) and \"Look Up\" (March 2007). The latter reached the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]] top&nbsp;100.<ref name=\"ARIA Report 888\">{{cite web | date = 12 March 2007 | archiveurl = https://webarchive.nla.gov.au/awa/20070319130000/http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/23790/20070320-0000/issue888.pdf | title = Week Commencing ~ 12th March 2007 ~ Issue #888 | last = Wallace | first = Ian | work = The ARIA Report | format = PDF | publisher = [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA) | issue = 888 | pages = 2, 4, 8, 10, 14, 19 | url = http://www.aria.com.au/pages/documents/issue888.pdf | archivedate = 20 March 2007 | accessdate = 13 April 2020 }} Note: Source incorrectly spells her name as \"Colette\" on page 2 but correctly thereafter. </ref> She appeared on the Australian TV show ''Cool Aid'' and performed \"Look Up\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvovermind.com/toni-collette/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Toni Collette|last=Hanson-Firestone|first=Dana|date=2019-10-17|website=TVOvermind|language=en-US|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> In July 2007 Toni Collette & the Finish headlined the Sydney show of [[Live Earth]], singing a cover of T. Rex's \"[[Children of the Revolution (song)|Children of the Revolution]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Sams|first=Christine|title=Sydney's giant, jolly green gig|url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/music/sydneys-giant-jolly-green-gig/2007/07/07/1183351525552.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=8 July 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"NLA Live Earth\">{{cite web | archiveurl = https://webarchive.nla.gov.au/awa/20090511174949/http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/58813/20090512-0004/www.boudist.com/gallery/v/gigs/live-earth-sydney/toni-collette-finish-03.JPG.html | url = http://www.boudist.com/gallery/v/gigs/live-earth-sydney/toni-collette-finish-03.JPG.html | title = 12 May 2009 - Toni Collette and the Finish: Live Earth Sydney @ Aussie Stadium 070707 : Boudist Photos | publisher = Trove | archive-date = 12 May 2009 | date = 7 July 2007 | access-date = 14 April 2020 }}</ref> They toured Australia,<ref name=\"Lantern\">{{cite web | url=http://thedwarf.com.au/nd/layout/set/print/news/national/toni_collette_and_the_finish_announce_tour | title = Toni Collette and The Finish Announce Tour | author = Lantern, Pearl | website = theDwarf | publication-date = 6 February 2007 | via=National Library of Australia | archiveurl=https://webarchive.nla.gov.au/awa/20080803001515/http://thedwarf.com.au/nd/layout/set/print/news/national/toni_collette_and_the_finish_announce_tour\n| archive-date = 3 August 2008 | access-date = 14 April 2020 }}</ref> but have not performed nor released any new material after 2007. In 2012 she expressed her desire to make another album, but said she found it difficult to find enough time to commit to that project.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite journal | url = https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/interview-toni-collette/ | title = Interview: Toni Collette on ''Hitchcock'', ''The Sixth Sense'', and More | last = Osenlund | first = R. Kurt | work = [[Slant Magazine]] | date = 24 November 2012 | accessdate = 15 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Humanitarian work==\n\n[[File:Toni Collette (6902409149) (cropped).jpg|alt=The 39-year-old is shown in an upper body shot and is facing her right. She has her left hand raised in a wave; it shows two rings on the fourth finger. She has strawberry-blonde, over-shoulder length hair. She has a black jacket over a white dress, which has black polka dots.|left|thumb|240x240px|Collette at the 2012 [[Tropfest]] in Sydney]]\nCollette supports various charities including [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|Doctors Without Borders]], [[Amnesty International]] and [[Feeding America]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.looktothestars.org/celebrity/toni-collette | title = Toni Collette: Charity Work & Causes | website = Look to the Stars | access-date = 14 March 2020 }}</ref> She expressed her support for [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals|PETA]] and, in July 2005, wrote a letter to then [[Prime Minister of Australia|Australian Prime Minister]] [[John Howard]], asking him to ban the practice of [[mulesing]] and the [[Australian live export industry|live export of sheep]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/movies/toni-not-sheepish-20050701-ge0fzc.html | title = Toni not Sheepish | date = 1 July 2005 | work = The Age | access-date = 14 March 2020 }}</ref> Later that month, after speaking to sheep farmers, she reneged on supporting PETA's campaign against mulesing: \"The issue is not as black and white as was previously presented to me. I was given to understand that there were 'effective and humane alternatives to prevent fly strike' and they are 'currently available.' I am now aware that there are no simple alternatives available to farmers at this time.\"<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite news | url = https://www.eonline.com/news/54011/pink-not-sheepish-on-wool-issue | title = Pink not Sheepish on Wool Issue | last = Hall | first = Sarah | work = [[E! News]] | date = 20 December 2006 | access-date = 15 April 2020  }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the actor auctioned off T-shirts of her own design to raise money for various charities.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.looktothestars.org/news/2677-celebrities-do-whatever-it-takes-for-charity | title = Celebrities Do Whatever It Takes for Charity | date = 15 June 2009 | website = Look to the Stars | access-date = 14 March 2020 }}</ref> Collette along with Drew Barrymore and [[Catherine Hardwicke]], who all worked together on ''Miss You Already'', wore [[Breast cancer awareness|pink ribbons]] to support [[Breast Cancer Awareness Month]] in October 2014.<ref name=\"Friedman\">{{cite journal | url = https://www.redbookmag.com/beauty-fashion/blogs/trends/toni-collette-shaved-head | title = Toni Collette Has a Bold New Look | last = Friedman | first = Megan | date = 10 October 2014 | work = Redbook | access-date = 15 March 2020 }}</ref> She has raised money for OzHarvest, an organisation which collects excess food from Australian restaurants and redistributes it to the homeless.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/celebrity/toni-collette-helps-aussie-food-charity/news-story/feb277c255798bca3ee0c186576b603e | title = Collette Helps Aussie Food Charity | date = 19 October 2009 | work = The Herald Sun | access-date = 15 March 2020 }}</ref> She sold some of her personal items for an auction to raise money for the charity Cure Our Kids, which is dedicated to raising money for the [[oncology]] unit at [[Royal Alexandra Hospital for Children|The Children's Hospital at Westmead]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.looktothestars.org/news/1469-lleyton-hewitt-launches-charity-auction | title = Lleyton Hewitt Launches Charity Auction | date = 28 October 2008 | website = Look to the Stars | access-date = 15 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, she was part of the host committee to hold the third annual Go Go Gala which will benefit the [[GO Campaign]] which seeks to help orphans and vulnerable children throughout the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/5375-ewan-mcgregor-to-host-celebrity-charity-go-go-gala|title=Ewan McGregor To Host Celebrity Charity Go Go Gala|date=2010-11-17|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> She took part in the promotion of the documentary ''[[The Lazarus Effect (2010 film)|The Lazarus Effect]]'' (2010), being featured in a small clip which sought to raise awareness of the positive impact of free [[antiretroviral drug]] therapy for those living with [[HIV]] in [[Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/4323-bono-leads-celebrity-psa-for-red-charity|title=Bono Leads Celebrity PSA For (RED) Charity|date=2010-05-02|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> In 2012, Collette has contributed an exclusive blog on the fight against hunger and a call to action for [[Giving Tuesday]] and the holiday season to the [[Huffington post|Huffington Post]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/9347-stars-support-giving-tuesday|title=Stars Support Giving Tuesday|date=2012-11-27|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, she was appointed as a global ambassador for [[Concern Worldwide]]. She made her first field visit with Concern to [[Haiti]] where she met families who, together with Concern, are working to break the cycle of extreme poverty. She had previously raised money for Concern\u2019s global campaign to fight hunger and malnutrition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.concernusa.org/story/toni-collette-is-concerns-new-global-ambassador/|title=Toni Collette is Concern\u2019s new global ambassador|website=Concern Worldwide|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> She has taken part in multiple [[Public service announcement|Public Service Announcements]] by Concern requesting the viewers to donate to Concern's various campaigns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/49709122|title=Toni Collette and Concern Worldwide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/52887032|title=Toni Collette presents the perfect gift|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2017, she attended the 25th Annual [[Elton John AIDS Foundation Academy Award Party]] which seeks to raise money to support innovative HIV prevention, education programs and direct care and support services to people living with HIV.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/16377-25th-annual-elton-john-aids-foundation-academy-awards-viewing-party-raises-record-breaking-7-million|title=25th Annual Elton John AIDS Foundation Academy Awards Viewing Party Raises Record-Breaking $7 Million|date=2017-02-28|website=Look to the Stars|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> She has expressed her support for the [[Me Too movement]].<ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== Artistry ==\n\nCollette is described by [[Toby Creswell]] and Samantha Trenoweth in their book, ''1001 Australians You Should Know'' (2006), \"she proved her abilities as a serious actress in Rowan Woods' 1998 film ''The Boys'' and again in the big budget international hits ''The Sixth Sense'' and ''About a Boy''.\"<ref name=\"Creswell\">{{cite book | title = 1001 Australians You Should Know | last = Creswell | first = Toby | authorlink = Toby Creswell | author2 = Samantha Trenoweth | publisher = Pluto Press Australia | year = 2006 | chapter = Arts and Popular Culture: Tony Collette | location = [[North Melbourne, Victoria]] | page = 63 | isbn = 978-1-86403-361-8 }}</ref> Sharon Waxman of ''The New York Times'' noted that the artist often embraces characters who are pathetic, insecure or otherwise unattractive.<ref name=\":6\" /> However, the actor said she detests playing such characters, \"If I keep perpetuating that image of myself \u2014 that of a downtrodden person \u2014 that's the only roles I'll get. And I'm getting tired of playing those roles.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> Despite achieving stardom early in her career with the top-grossing, ''The Sixth Sense'', she rarely acted in commerce-driven pictures. She prefers working in [[independent film]]s over [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbusters]] where the latter prioritize box-office success over telling a story.<ref name=\":7\" /> Several journalists noted her gravitation towards playing dissatisfied and slightly neurotic mothers. When asked about being [[Typecasting|typecast]] in such roles, Collette replied, \"All people are different. All women are different. A lot of women haven't had children but it doesn't change the fact that they're individuals and have some kind of individuality and spark about them.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Wise | first = Damon | url = https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/apr/16/toni-collette-every-scene-was-like-being-punched-glassland | title  =Toni Collette: 'Every scene was like being punched' | date = 16 April 2015 | work = The Guardian | access-date = 4 March 2020 | issn = 0261-3077}}</ref>{{Quote box\n| quote = \"I try to put myself in the position of the character and feel things as holistically as I can. It\u2019s an exhausting way to do it. I\u2019m not [going to] recommend it to anybody, but that\u2019s the only way I know how to do it.\"\n| source = {{snd}} Collette on her acting style<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vulture.com/2018/06/toni-collette-on-hereditary-the-wildest-movie-of-her-career.html | title = Toni Collette on ''Hereditary'', the Wildest Movie of Her Career | last = Handler | first = Rachel | date = 8 June 2018 | website = Vulture | access-date = 15 February 2020 }}</ref>\n| align = right\n| width = 20%\n| bgcolor = #E0E6F8\n}}Collette listed Geoffrey Rush as one of her influences and remembered seeing him in ''The Diary of a Madman'' (1989): \"When I watched him in that, it was like being in church, I had a full-on spiritual awakening. I even wrote him this letter \u2013 I don't remember what it said, but it was very complimentary.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> She does not find it difficult to detach herself from her roles, but reflected that after doing several heavy thematic films she, \"[started] to find things were accumulating. I had to figure out a way to kind of shake it off. So I am figuring that out.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.slashfilm.com/toni-collette-hereditary-interview/ | title = Toni Collette Tells Us the Scariest Thing About ''Hereditary''  &#91;Interview&#93; | last = Pearson | first = Ben | date = 8 June 2018 | website = [[/Film]] | access-date = 16 April 2020 }}</ref> When asked how she decides to play her characters, she replied, \"When I look at a character, I never look at the size of the role. I always look at the whole person, no matter how much they're featured in the movie.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://nowtoronto.com/movies/features/q-and-a-toni-collette/ | title = Q&A: Toni Collette Actor, ''Hostages'' and ''Enough Said'' | last = Cole | first = Susan G. | date = 23 September 2013 | work = [[Now (newspaper)|Now]] | location = [[Toronto]] | access-date = 16 April 2020 }}</ref> She prefers not to work with [[dialect coach]]es, when preparing for an accent, as they usualy make her feel self-conscious.<ref>{{cite web | title = Art of Film: Accents, Dialects and Acting with Saoirse Ronan & Toni Collette| publisher = Sundance Institute YouTube | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3QFFnFtQufM | date = 26 January 2015 | access-date = 6 March 2020 }}</ref> Although she has gained weight to play characters in previous films, she dislikes doing so, and after filming ''In Her Shoes'', said that she would never do so again.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/toni-collette-worth-the-weight-326193.html | title = Toni Collette: Worth the Weight | date = 11 November 2005 | work = [[The Independent]] | access-date = 4 March 2020 }}</ref> [[Brie Larson]], who starred with Collette in ''United States of Tara'', has cited her as an inspiration and praised her for being able to \"disappear\" into her roles.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cBTvu66vc7g | title = THR Roundtable {{!}} Play the video at 7:58 for the quote |last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Greg Kinnear]], her co-star in ''Dinner with Friends'' and ''Little Miss Sunshine,'' called her \"gifted\" and commended her for being able to communicate without dialogue.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nRilla Kingston in an analysis of Collette's acting style, compared her to character actress [[Thelma Ritter]] who was also widely critically acclaimed for her supporting roles and repeatedly typecast as the female comic second. Kingston took note of Collette's use of physicality to convey her characters' emotions as in ''Emma'' and ''United States of Tara''. She remarked that Collette's acting method references the components of [[Stanislavski's system|Stanislavski\u2019s System of Acting]]. In studying Collette's typecasting as mothers, Kingston wrote, \"[Collette] selectively chooses roles of women and mothers which she can portray in ways that are multidimensional and different from another.\" She also wrote that Collette makes conscious efforts to break from the typecasting, with leading roles in films like ''Miss You Already'' and ''Lucky Them''. At the end of her analysis, Kingston concluded, \"Collette truly is a chameleon in both the versatility of her acting style and in the kind of roles she is willing to approach with a physicality-based method.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mcgillchannelundergraduatereview.com/2018/04/toni-collette-character-as-craft/|title=Toni Collette: Character as Craft \u2013 The Channel|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n[[File:Toni Collette by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|236x236px|Collette at the 2015 [[San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic Con]] promoting [[Krampus (film)|''Krampus'']] (2015)|alt=]]\n\nIn her twenties she found it difficult to adapt to being in the media spotlight and, as a result, struggled with [[Bulimia nervosa|bulimia]] and [[panic attack]]s.<ref name=\":1\" /> During this period she travelled extensively, shaved her head five times and bought a flat in [[Brixton]], London. Her aim was to \"explore different ideas and just look at life and try to understand it.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> She left the Brixton flat after a few months because she saw a man \"getting his head bashed in with a pole 30 metres away.\"<ref name=\":11\" /> Collette had dated her ''Velvet Goldmine'' co-star, [[Jonathan Rhys Meyers]], for about a year ([[Circa|ca.]] 1997) before ending their relationship and described it as \"hedonistic, drunken and probably dangerous.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> When asked about her faith, she remarked, \"We're all spiritual... I'm not [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] but I am drawn to it because it seems the most beneficial of organised religions, and the most compassionate. It's an ongoing journey.\"\n\nShe met musician Dave Galafassi early in 2002,<ref name=\"SMH Jan03\">{{cite news | url = https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/tonis-wedding-20030112-gdg3fr.html | title = Toni's Wedding | work = The Sydney Morning Herald | date = 12 January 2003 | access-date = 8 April 2020 }}</ref> at a CD launch for his then-band [[Gelbison]],<ref name=\":10\" /> the couple married in a traditional Buddhist ceremony on 11 January 2003.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benns|first=Matthew|last2=Sams|first2=Christine|title=Toni's wedding|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/01/12/1041990146127.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=12 January 2003}}</ref> The couple have a daughter, Sage Florence, born on 9 January 2008,<ref>{{cite news|last=Tan|first=Michelle|title=Toni Collette Has a Girl|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20170375,00.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=10 January 2008}}</ref> and a son, Arlo Robert, born on 22 April 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chi|first=Paul|last2=Jordan|first2=Julie|title=Toni Collette Is a Mom \u2013 Again!|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20484453,00.html|accessdate=11 December 2013|newspaper=People|date=25 April 2011}}</ref> She has said that she is an avid camper and she enjoys meditating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indexmagazine.com/interviews/toni_collette.shtml|title=Toni Collette with Ariana Speyer|last=|first=|date=|website=www.indexmagazine.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> They lived in Sydney in the 2000s before moving to Los Angeles.<ref name=\":11\" /> The family returned to Sydney after about ten years in 2019.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\"Graham\">{{cite web | url = https://www.news.com.au/entertainment/toni-collettes-husband-injured-in-devastating-accident/news-story/8ccff92c6fee5121b73641b9d67f87f9 | title = Toni Collette\u2019s husband injured in \u2018devastating accident\u2019 | last = Graham | first = Ben | work = news.com.au | date = 28 December 2019 | accessdate = 8 April 2020 }}</ref> In December of that year Galafassi \"had a devastating motorbike accident\"; Collette thanked the ambulance services, \"for your swiftness, clarity, knowledge, compassion and dedication. You saved him and we cannot thank you enough.\"<ref name=\"Graham\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!  scope=\"col\" | Title\n!  scope=\"col\" | Year\n!  scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Spotswood (film)|Spotswood]]''\n| 1992\n| Wendy Robinson\n| {{Abbr|a.k.a.|also known as}} ''The Efficiency Expert''\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''This Marching Girl Thing''\n| 1994\n| Cindy\n| Short film\n| <ref name=\"BFI Filmography\">{{cite web | url = https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2baa9ceae7 | title = Toni Collette | publisher = [[British Film Institute|BFI]] | access-date = 9 April 2020 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Muriel's Wedding]]''\n| 1994\n| Muriel Heslop/Mariel Heslop/Mariel Heslop-Van Arkle\n|\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Thief and the Cobbler]]''\n| 1995\n| Princess Yum Yum's Nanny Witch\n|  {{Abbr|a.k.a.|also known as}} ''Arabian Knight'', Voice (Miramax version)\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"BFI Filmography\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Clockers (film)|Clockers]]''\n| 1995\n| Virginia Martin\n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Cos\u00ec (film)|Cos\u00ec]]''\n| 1996\n| Julie\n|\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"BFI Filmography\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Pallbearer]]''\n| 1996\n| Cynthia\n|\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"BFI Filmography\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Emma (1996 theatrical film)|Emma]]''\n| 1996\n| Harriet Smith\n|\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"Metacritic film list\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Lilian's Story]]''\n| 1996\n| Young Lilian Singer\n|\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"BFI Filmography\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Clockwatchers]]''\n| 1997\n| Iris Chapman\n|\n| <ref name=\"Flint Marx\"/><ref name=\"BFI Filmography\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''The James Gang''\n| 1997\n| Julia A