season]], Division Two).\n*Fewest league goals conceded in a season: '''26''' (in 22 matches in the [[1947\u201348 in Scottish football|1947\u201348 season]], [[Scottish Football League Division C|Division C]]).\n\n===Points===\n*Most points in a season:\n**Two points for a win: '''55''' (in 38 matches in the [[1931\u201332 in Scottish football|1931\u201332 season]], Division Two).\n**Three points for a win: '''67''' (in 30 matches in the [[2016\u201317 in Scottish football|2016-17]] season, [[Scottish Lowland Football League]]).\n*Fewest points in a season:\n**Two points for a win:\n***'''12''' (in 22 matches in the [[1905\u201306 in Scottish football|1905\u201306 season]], Division Two).\n***'''12''' (in 34 matches in the [[1963\u201364 in Scottish football|1963\u201364 season]], [[Scottish Football League Division One|Division One]]).\n**Three points for a win:\n***'''8''' (in 36 matches in the [[2003\u201304 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]], Third Division).\n\n===Matches===\n\n====Firsts====\n*First match as ''Britannia'': '''Britannia 0\u20137 [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk 2nd XI]]''', 4 December 1880.\n*First match as ''East Stirlingshire'':  '''[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] 5\u20130 East Stirlingshire''', 27 August 1881.\n*First league match: '''East Stirlingshire 2\u20133 [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]''', 18 August 1900.\n*First [[Lowland Football League]] match: East Stirlingshire 2-2 [[Vale of Leithen F.C.|Vale of Leithen]], 6 August 2016.\n*First Scottish Cup match: '''Milngavie Thistle 2\u20131 East Stirlingshire''', September 1882.\n*First Scottish League Cup match: '''East Stirlingshire 2\u20131 [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]''', 11 September 1948.\n*First Scottish Challenge Cup match: '''[[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] 5\u20130 East Stirlingshire''', 16 October 1990.\n\n====Record wins====\n*Record [[Scottish Football League]] win: '''8\u20130''' (against [[Arthurlie F.C.|Arthurlie]], 27 August 1927).\n*Record Scottish Football League away win: '''6\u20130''' (against [[Bo'ness F.C.|Bo'ness]], 24 January 1921; and against [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]], 10 September 1955).\n*Record [[Scottish Cup]] win: \n**'''10\u20131''' (against [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]], 1 September 1888); \n**'''11\u20132''' (against [[Vale of Bannock F.C.|Vale of Bannock]], 22 September 1888).\n*Record [[Scottish League Cup]] win: \n**'''4\u20130''' (against [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]], 1 September 1976);\n**'''5\u20131''' (against Berwick Rangers, 31 August 1957; and against [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], 15 August 1959);\n**'''6\u20132''' (against [[East Fife F.C.|East Fife]], 4 September 1965).\n*Record [[Lowland Football League]] win: 10-1 (against [[Gala Fairydean Rovers F.C.|Gala Fairydean Rovers]], Saturday 3 December 2016).\n*Record [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] win: '''4\u20130''' (against Stenhousemuir, 12 September 2000).\n*Record win in any match: '''17\u20130''' (against Carron, [[Stirlingshire Cup]], 18 October 1884).\n\n====Record defeats====\n*Record Scottish Football League defeat: '''1\u201312''' (against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], 13 April 1936).\n*Record Scottish Cup defeat: '''2\u201310''' (against [[Renton F.C.|Renton]], 4 April 1884).\n*Record Scottish League Cup defeat: '''2\u20139''' (against [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]], 18 August 1956).\n*Record Scottish Challenge Cup defeat: '''0\u20137''' (against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], 6 August 2002).\n\n===Record consecutive results===\n*Record consecutive league wins: '''8''' (from 14 November 2009 to 10 February 2010).\n*Record consecutive league defeats: '''24''' (from 8 November 2003 to 8 May 2004).\n*Record consecutive league games without a defeat: '''17''' (from 19 November 2017 to 31 March 2018).\n*Record consecutive league games without a win: '''26''' (from 8 February 2003 to 25 October 2003).\n\n===Attendances===\n*Highest attendance at [[Firs Park]]:\n**Scottish Cup game: '''12,000''' (against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], 19 February 1921).\n**League game: '''10,000''' (against St Mirren, 16 November 1935).\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"note\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{East Stirlingshire F.C.}}\n{{Scottish football club records}}\n\n[[Category:East Stirlingshire F.C.|Records]]\n[[Category:Scottish football club statistics|East Stirlingshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|all-time records|a season-by-season statistical breakdown|List of East Stirlingshire F.C. seasons}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n\n[[East Stirlingshire F.C.]] is a Scottish [[association football]] club from [[Falkirk]].  The club was founded in 1881 joined the [[Scottish Football League]] in 1900.\n\nThis list encompasses the major honours won by East Stirlingshire, records set by the club, its managers and its players. The player records section includes details of the club's leading goalscorers and those who have made most appearances in first-team competitions. It also records notable achievements by East Stirlingshire players in international tournaments, and the highest transfer fees paid and received by the club. Attendance records at [[Firs Park]], the club's home ground between 1921 and 2008, are also included in the list.\n\n==Honours==\n'''League'''\n*'''[[Scottish Football League Division Two|Division Two]]''' (before 1975) and '''[[Scottish Football League First Division|First Division]]''' (after 1975):\n**'''[[List of winners of the Scottish First Division and predecessors|Winners]] (1)''': [[1931\u201332 in Scottish football|1931\u201332]]\n**'''Runners-up (1)''': [[1962\u201363 in Scottish football|1962\u201363]]\n*'''[[Scottish Football League Division Three|Division Three]]''' (1923 to 1926), '''[[Scottish Football League Division C|Division C]]''' (1946 to 1949) and '''[[Scottish Football League Second Division|Second Division]]''' (after 1975):\n**'''[[List of winners of the Scottish Second Division and predecessors|Winners]] (1)''': [[1947\u201348 in Scottish football|1947\u201348]]\n**'''Runners-up (2)''': [[1923\u201324 in Scottish football|1923\u201324]], [[1979\u201380 in Scottish football|1979\u201380]]\n** Runners-up (3) : 2016-17 in [[Lowland Football League]].\n\n==Player records==\n{{see also|List of East Stirlingshire F.C. players}}\n\n===Most appearances===\n\n:''Scottish Football League appearances from 1948 to 2013 only.''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n!width=6%|#\n!style=\"width:20%\"|Name\n!style=\"width:15%\"|Nationality\n!Position<ref group = \"note\">For a full description of positions see: [[Association football positions]].</ref>\n!East Stirlingshire <br>career\n!League <br>appearances\n!League goals\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|1\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Gordon|Russell|Gordon Russell (footballer)}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|DF\n|1986\u20132002\n|445\n|9\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player4/gordonrussell.html |title=GORDON   RUSSELL |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|2\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Derek |Ure|Derek Ure footballer) }}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|MF\n|2002-2011, 2016-2018\n|400\n|33\n|\n|-\n|3\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Gordon |Simpson|Gordon Simpson}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|DF\n|1967-1981\n|376\n|23\n|-\n|4\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Jim|Meakin}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|MF\n|1969\u20131985\n|272\n|32\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player2/jimmeakin.html|title=JIM   MEAKIN |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|5\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Ian|Rennie}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|DF\n|1978\u20131988\n|272\n|24\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player3/ianrennie.html |title=IAN   RENNIE |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|6\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Bobby|McCulley}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|MF\n|1972\u20131991\n|268\n|30\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player1/bobmcculley.html |title=BOB   McCULLEY |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=17 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|7\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Arthur|Hammill}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|MF\n|1962\u20131971\n|266\n|39\n|\n|-\n|8\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Tom|Craig|Tom Craig (footballer)}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|DF\n|1960\u20131968\n|259\n|0\n|\n|-\n|9\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Charlie|Kelly|Charlie Kelly (footballer)}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|GK\n|1978\u20131990\n|222\n|1\n|<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player3/charliekelly.html |title=CHARLIE   KELLY |publisher=Neil Brown |accessdate=17 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n|10\n|align=\"left\"|{{sortname|Tom|Donnelly|Tom Donnelly (footballer)}}\n|align=\"left\"|{{SCO}}\n|MF\n|1971\u20131978\n|216\n|26\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Goalscorers===\n*Most league goals in one season: '''41''', [[Andy Rodgers]] in the [[2016-17 Lowland Football League]].\n\n===International caps===\n*First capped player: [[Humphrey Jones]] for [[Wales national football team|Wales]] against [[England national football team|England]] on 23 February 1889.\n*First capped player for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]: Archibald Ritchie against Wales on 21 March 1891.\n*Most capped player: Humphrey Jones with 5 caps for Wales as an East Stirlingshire player.\n*Most capped player for Scotland: [[David Alexander (footballer)|David Alexander]], 2 caps as an East Stirlingshire player.\n\n===Transfers===\n*Record transfer fee paid: '''\u00a36,000''' for Colin McKinnon from [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], 1991.{{Citation needed|date=March 2013}}\n*Record transfer fee received: '''\u00a335,000''' for [[Jim Docherty]] to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]], 1978.\n\n==Club records==\n\n===Goals===\n*Most league goals scored in a season: '''111''' (in 38 matches in the [[1931\u201332 in Scottish football|1931\u201332 season]], [[Scottish Football League Division Two|Division Two]]).\n*Fewest league goals scored in a season: '''21''' (in 22 matches in the [[1911\u201312 in Scottish football|1911\u201312 season]], Division Two).\n*Most league goals conceded in a season: '''121''' (in 36 matches in the [[1956\u201357 in Scottish football|1956\u201357 season]], Division Two).\n*Fewest league goals conceded in a season: '''26''' (in 22 matches in the [[1947\u201348 in Scottish football|1947\u201348 season]], [[Scottish Football League Division C|Division C]]).\n\n===Points===\n*Most points in a season:\n**Two points for a win: '''55''' (in 38 matches in the [[1931\u201332 in Scottish football|1931\u201332 season]], Division Two).\n**Three points for a win: '''67''' (in 30 matches in the [[2016\u201317 in Scottish football|2016-17]] season, [[Scottish Lowland Football League]]).\n*Fewest points in a season:\n**Two points for a win:\n***'''12''' (in 22 matches in the [[1905\u201306 in Scottish football|1905\u201306 season]], Division Two).\n***'''12''' (in 34 matches in the [[1963\u201364 in Scottish football|1963\u201364 season]], [[Scottish Football League Division One|Division One]]).\n**Three points for a win:\n***'''8''' (in 36 matches in the [[2003\u201304 in Scottish football|2003\u201304 season]], Third Division).\n\n===Matches===\n\n====Firsts====\n*First match as ''Britannia'': '''Britannia 0\u20137 [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk 2nd XI]]''', 4 December 1880.\n*First match as ''East Stirlingshire'':  '''[[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] 5\u20130 East Stirlingshire''', 27 August 1881.\n*First league match: '''East Stirlingshire 2\u20133 [[Airdrieonians F.C. (1878)|Airdrieonians]]''', 18 August 1900.\n*First [[Lowland Football League]] match: East Stirlingshire 2-2 [[Vale of Leithen F.C.|Vale of Leithen]], 6 August 2016.\n*First Scottish Cup match: '''Milngavie Thistle 2\u20131 East Stirlingshire''', September 1882.\n*First Scottish League Cup match: '''East Stirlingshire 2\u20131 [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]''', 11 September 1948.\n*First Scottish Challenge Cup match: '''[[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] 5\u20130 East Stirlingshire''', 16 October 1990.\n\n====Record wins====\n*Record [[Scottish Football League]] win: '''8\u20130''' (against [[Arthurlie F.C.|Arthurlie]], 27 August 1927).\n*Record Scottish Football League away win: '''6\u20130''' (against [[Bo'ness F.C.|Bo'ness]], 24 January 1921; and against [[Berwick Rangers F.C.|Berwick Rangers]], 10 September 1955).\n*Record [[Scottish Cup]] win: \n**'''10\u20131''' (against [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]], 1 September 1888); \n**'''11\u20132''' (against [[Vale of Bannock F.C.|Vale of Bannock]], 22 September 1888).\n*Record [[Scottish League Cup]] win: \n**'''4\u20130''' (against [[Cowdenbeath F.C.|Cowdenbeath]], 1 September 1976);\n**'''5\u20131''' (against Berwick Rangers, 31 August 1957; and against [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]], 15 August 1959);\n**'''6\u20132''' (against [[East Fife F.C.|East Fife]], 4 September 1965).\n*Record [[Lowland Football League]] win: 10-1 (against [[Gala Fairydean Rovers F.C.|Gala Fairydean Rovers]], Saturday 3 December 2016).\n*Record [[Scottish Challenge Cup]] win: '''4\u20130''' (against Stenhousemuir, 12 September 2000).\n*Record win in any match: '''17\u20130''' (against Carron, [[Stirlingshire Cup]], 18 October 1884).\n\n====Record defeats====\n*Record Scottish Football League defeat: '''1\u201312''' (against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], 13 April 1936).\n*Record Scottish Cup defeat: '''2\u201310''' (against [[Renton F.C.|Renton]], 4 April 1884).\n*Record Scottish League Cup defeat: '''2\u20139''' (against [[Albion Rovers F.C.|Albion Rovers]], 18 August 1956).\n*Record Scottish Challenge Cup defeat: '''0\u20137''' (against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], 6 August 2002).\n\n===Record consecutive results===\n*Record consecutive league wins: '''8''' (from 14 November 2009 to 10 February 2010).\n*Record consecutive league defeats: '''24''' (from 8 November 2003 to 8 May 2004).\n*Record consecutive league games without a defeat: '''17''' (from 19 November 2017 to 31 March 2018).\n*Record consecutive league games without a win: '''26''' (from 8 February 2003 to 25 October 2003).\n\n===Attendances===\n*Highest attendance at [[Firs Park]]:\n**Scottish Cup game: '''12,000''' (against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]], 19 February 1921).\n**League game: '''10,000''' (against St Mirren, 16 November 1935).\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"note\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{East Stirlingshire F.C.}}\n{{Scottish football club records}}\n\n[[Category:East Stirlingshire F.C.|Records]]\n[[Category:Scottish football club statistics|East Stirlingshire]]\n", "name_user": "Paine Ellsworth", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMost appearances:dablink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_East_Stirlingshire_F.C._records_and_statistics"}
{"title_page": "Sogdian language", "text_new": "{{short description|Extinct Eastern Iranian language of Central Asia}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Sogdian\n|nativename=''su\u03b3\u03b4\u012bk'', ''\ud803\udf3c\ud803\udf34\ud803\udf36\ud803\udf39\ud803\udf37\ud803\udf38'' <ref name = \"Pandey2017\">{{cite web |last1=Pandey |first1=Anshuman |title=Revised proposal to encode the Sogdian script in Unicode |url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2016/16371r2-sogdian.pdf |date=25 January 2017|accessdate=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n|state=[[Sogdia]]\n|region=[[Central Asia]], [[China]]\n|era=100 BCE \u2013 1000 CE\n|ref=linglist\n|speakers2=developed into modern [[Yaghnobi language|Yaghnobi]]\n|familycolor=Indo-European\n|fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]]\n|fam3=[[Iranian languages|Iranian]]\n|fam4=[[Eastern Iranian languages|Eastern]]?<ref name=\"Gernet1996\">{{cite book|author=Jacques Gernet|title=A History of Chinese Civilization|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofchinese00gern|url-access=registration|date=31 May 1996|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-49781-7|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofchinese00gern/page/282 282]\u2013}}</ref>\n|fam5=Northern\n|script={{plainlist|\n*[[Sogdian alphabet]]\n*[[Syriac alphabet]]<ref name=\"LaetHerrmann1996\">{{cite book|author1=Sigfried J. de Laet|author2=Joachim Herrmann|title=History of Humanity: From the seventh century B.C. to the seventh century A.D.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WGUz01yBumEC&pg=PA467&lpg=PA467&dq=afshin+sogdian&source=bl&ots=fnFtMyDEx8&sig=4-tNWX8tvUW0MDeOHFv1pooGMDU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwpp_bvO3OAhWLXB4KHRoCBz4Q6AEIHjAA#v=onepage&q=afshin%20sogdian&f=false|date=1 January 1996|publisher=UNESCO|isbn=978-92-3-102812-0|pages=467\u2013}}</ref>\n*[[Manichaean alphabet]]}}\n|iso2=sog\n|iso3=sog\n|glotto=sogd1245\n|glottorefname=Sogdian\n}}\n[[File:Sogdian text Manichaean letter.jpg|thumb|Sogdian text from a Manichaean [[creditor]] letter from around 9th to 13th century|350px]]\n[[Image:Manicheans.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Manichaeism|Manichaean]] priests writing Sogdian manuscripts, in [[Gaochang|Khocho]], [[Tarim Basin]], c. 8th/9th century AD]]\n[[File:Sogdian-fragment-ca. 700 AD.jpg|thumb|Fragment of a Sogdian silk [[brocade]], c. 700 AD|upright]]\n[[File:BezeklikSogdianMerchants.jpg|thumb|Sogdians donors to the Buddha (fresco, with detail), [[Bezeklik]], eastern [[Tarim Basin]], China, 8th century.]]\n[[File:Westerner on a camel.jpg|thumb|200px|A [[Tang Dynasty]] [[Chinese ceramic]] statuette of a Sogdian merchant riding on a [[Bactrian camel]]]]\n\nThe '''Sogdian language''' was an [[Eastern Iranian languages|Eastern Iranian language]] spoken mainly in the [[Central Asia]]n region of [[Sogdia]] (capital: [[Samarkand]]; other chief cities: [[Panjakent]], [[Fergana]], [[Khujand]], and [[Bukhara]]), located in modern-day [[Uzbekistan]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Kazakhstan]]<ref>https://sogdians.si.edu/sidebars/sogdian-language/</ref> and [[Kyrgyzstan]]<ref>Barthold, W. \"Bal\u0101s\u0101g\u0332h\u0332\u016bn or Bal\u0101sa\u1e33\u016bn.\" Encyclopaedia of Islam. Edited by: P. Bearman , Th. Bianquis , C.E. Bosworth , E. van Donzel and W.P. Heinrichs. Brill, 2008. Brill Online. Universiteitsbibliotheek Leiden. 11 March 2008 <http://www.brillonline.nl/subscriber/entry?entry=islam_SIM-1131></ref><ref>[[Sogdia]]</ref>; it was also spoken by some Sogdian immigrant communities in ancient China. Sogdian is one of the most important [[Iranian languages#Middle Iranian languages|Middle Iranian languages]], along with [[Bactrian language|Bactrian]], [[Saka language|Khotanese Saka]], [[Middle Persian]], and [[Parthian language|Parthian]]. It possesses a large literary corpus.\n\nThe Sogdian language is usually assigned to a Northeastern group of the [[Iranian languages]]. No direct evidence of an earlier version of the language (\"Old Sogdian\") has been found, although mention of the area in the [[Old Persian]] inscriptions means that a separate and recognisable Sogdia existed at least since the [[Achaemenid Empire]] (559\u2013323 BCE).\n\nLike Khotanese, Sogdian possesses a more conservative [[grammar]] and [[morphology (linguistics)|morphology]] than Middle Persian {{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}. The modern Eastern Iranian language [[Yaghnobi language|Yaghnobi]] is the descendant of a dialect of Sogdian spoken around the 8th century in [[Osrushana]], a region to the south of Sogdia.\n\n==History==\nDuring [[Tang dynasty|Tang China]] (ca. 7th century CE), the [[Silk Road]]'s [[lingua franca]] in Central Asia was Sogdian, <ref name=\"Lung2011\">{{cite book|author=Rachel Lung|title=Interpreters in Early Imperial China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wa5xAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA151#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=7 September 2011|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing Company|isbn=978-90-272-8418-1|pages=151\u2013}}</ref><ref>[[Eliot Weinberger|Weinberger, E.]], \"[http://www.nybooks.com/articles/22032 China's Golden Age]\", [[The New York Review of Books]], 55:17. Retrieved on 2008-10-19.</ref> along which it amassed a rich vocabulary by [[loanword]]s such as ''tym'' (\"hotel\") from the [[Middle Chinese]] /tem/ ({{zh|[[wikt:\u5e97|\u5e97]]}}).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Silk Road: A New History|first=Valerie|last=Hanson|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2012|page=136}}</ref>\n\nThe economic and political importance of Sogdian guaranteed its survival in the first few centuries after the [[Muslim conquests|Muslim conquest of Sogdia]] in the early eighth century. <ref>[[Richard Foltz]], ''A History of the Tajiks: Iranians of the East'', London: [[Bloomsbury]], 2019, pp. 4-5.</ref> A dialect of Sogdian spoken around the 8th century in [[Osrushana]] (capital: Bunjikat, near present-day [[Istaravshan]], Tajikistan), a region to the south of Sogdia, developed into [[Yaghnobi language]] and has survived into the 21st century.<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=6\u2013}}</ref> It is spoken by the [[Yaghnobi people]].\n\n==Discovery of Sogdian texts==\n[[File:Sogdian Christian Text Written in Estrangelo.jpg|thumb|Sogdian [[Church of the East|Christian]] text written in [[Estrangelo]], discovered at [[Turpan]], 9th\u201411th century.]]\nThe finding of manuscript fragments of the Sogdian language in China's [[Xinjiang]] region sparked the study of the Sogdian language. [[Robert Gauthiot]], (the first Buddhist Sogdian scholar) and [[Paul Pelliot]], (who while exploring in [[Dunhuang]], retrieved Sogdian material) began investigating the Sogdian material that Pelliot had discovered. Gauthiot published many articles based on his work with Pelliot's material, but died during the First World War. One of Gauthiot's most impressive articles was a glossary to the Sogdian text, which he was in the process of completing when he died. This work was continued by [[\u00c9mile Benveniste]] after Gauthiot's death.<ref name=Utz>Utz, David. (1978). ''Survey of Buddhist Sogdian studies.'' Tokyo: The Reiyukai Library.</ref>\n\nVarious Sogdian pieces have been found in the Turfan text corpus by the [[German Turfan expeditions]]. These expeditions were controlled by the [[Ethnological Museum of Berlin]].<ref name=Utz /> These pieces consist almost entirely of religious works by Manichaean and Christian writers, including [[Bible translations into Sogdian|translations of the Bible]]. Most of the Sogdian religious works are from the 9th and 10th centuries.<ref name=iranian>''[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/293577/Iranian-languages/74634/The-Middle-Iranian-stage#ref=603453 \"Iranian Languages\"]''(2009). [[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]. Retrieved on 2009-04-09</ref>\n\nDunhuang and Turfan were the two most plentiful sites of Manichean, Buddhist, and Christian Sogdian texts. Sogdiana itself actually contained a much smaller collection of texts. These texts were business related, belonging to a minor Sogdian king, [[Divashtich]]. These business texts dated back to the time of the Muslim conquest, about 700.<ref name=iranian />\n\n==Writing system==\nLike all the writing systems employed for Middle Iranian languages, the [[Sogdian alphabet]] ultimately derives from the [[Aramaic alphabet]]. Like its close relatives, the [[Pahlavi scripts]], written Sogdian contains many [[logogram]]s or [[ideogram]]s, which were Aramaic words written to represent native spoken ones. The Sogdian script is the direct ancestor of the [[Old Uyghur alphabet]], itself the forerunner of the [[Traditional Mongolian alphabet]].\n\nAs in other writing systems descended from the [[Proto-Sinaitic script]], there are no special signs for vowels. As in the parent Aramaic system, the consonantal signs \u2019 y w can be used as [[mater lectionis|matres lectionis]] for the long vowels [a: i: u:] respectively. However, unlike it, these consonant signs would also sometimes serve to express the short vowels (which could also sometimes be left unexpressed, as they ''always'' are in the parent systems).<ref name=clauson/> To distinguish long vowels from short ones, an additional aleph could be written before the sign denoting the long vowel.<ref name=clauson>Clauson, Gerard. 2002. Studies in Turkic and Mongolic linguistics. P.103-104.</ref>\n\nThe Sogdian language also used the [[Manichaean alphabet]], which consisted of 29 letters.<ref>Gershevitch, Ilya. (1954). ''A Grammar of Manichean Sogdian.'' p.1. Oxford: Blackwell.</ref>\n\nIn transcribing Sogdian script into Roman letters, Aramaic ideograms are often noted by means of capitals.\n\n==Morphology==\n\n===Nouns===\n\n====Light stems====\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! Case || masc. ''a''-stems || neut. ''a''-stems || fem. ''\u0101''-stems || masc. ''u''-stems || fem. ''\u016b''-stems || masc. ''ya''-stems || fem. ''y\u0101''-stems || p